WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.532 align:middle line:90%


00:00:13.532 --> 00:00:14.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hi, and welcome.

00:00:14.740 --> 00:00:15.970 align:middle line:90%
I'm Lisa Garr.

00:00:15.970 --> 00:00:18.240 align:middle line:84%
The concept of
near-death experiences,

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:21.490 align:middle line:84%
where someone goes
to the flashing light

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:24.207 align:middle line:84%
before their eyes, and they see
their life flash before them,

00:00:24.207 --> 00:00:26.540 align:middle line:84%
and then they go down the
tunnel and they see the passed

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:29.970 align:middle line:84%
loved ones-- that whole
classic definition

00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:33.690 align:middle line:84%
was brought to us by my guest
today, Dr. Raymond Moody.

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:35.550 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Moody is the
author of a book called

00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:39.055 align:middle line:84%
"Life After Life,"
now in its 37th year.

00:00:39.055 --> 00:00:42.050 align:middle line:84%
It has sold millions of
copies because people

00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:45.920 align:middle line:84%
are really, truly curious
about the phenomenon

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:48.130 align:middle line:90%
of the near-death experience.

00:00:48.130 --> 00:00:51.035 align:middle line:84%
So welcome, and thank you so
much for joining me today.

00:00:51.035 --> 00:00:52.410 align:middle line:84%
>>RAYMOND MOODY:
Thank you, Lisa.

00:00:52.410 --> 00:00:54.310 align:middle line:84%
I just really appreciate
this invitation.

00:00:54.310 --> 00:00:55.050 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:00:55.050 --> 00:00:55.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:56.920 align:middle line:90%
Gosh, absolutely.

00:00:56.920 --> 00:00:59.320 align:middle line:84%
37 years ago, you
wrote this book.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:03.550 align:middle line:84%
What was the inspiration
behind "Life After Life"?

00:01:03.550 --> 00:01:06.290 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Basically, in
a word, it was Plato.

00:01:06.290 --> 00:01:09.370 align:middle line:84%
I was one of these
kids that-- I just

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:11.730 align:middle line:84%
wasn't exposed to
religion when I was young.

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:15.810 align:middle line:84%
And I'd become an amateur
astronomer at the age of seven

00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:17.950 align:middle line:84%
and never had thought
about life after death.

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:22.430 align:middle line:84%
But in 1962, when I was a
first-year undergraduate

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:24.380 align:middle line:84%
student at the
University of Virginia,

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:26.970 align:middle line:84%
I decided to be a
philosophy major,

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.460 align:middle line:90%
and reading Plato's "Republic".

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:33.360 align:middle line:84%
And Plato argues
very convincingly

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:35.570 align:middle line:84%
that this question
of life after death

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:39.460 align:middle line:84%
is the most important
question of human existence.

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:41.550 align:middle line:90%
And I was persuaded by that.

00:01:41.550 --> 00:01:44.072 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: He discussed that
hundreds and thousands of years

00:01:44.072 --> 00:01:44.572 align:middle line:90%
ago.

00:01:44.572 --> 00:01:45.820 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: 2,300 years ago.

00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:47.360 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of
"The Republic,"

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:49.670 align:middle line:84%
there's this account
of a warrior named

00:01:49.670 --> 00:01:52.330 align:middle line:84%
Er, who was believed
dead on the battlefield,

00:01:52.330 --> 00:01:56.240 align:middle line:84%
but during the funeral he
actually revived, and sat

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:59.940 align:middle line:84%
up, and described going into
another world where he saw

00:01:59.940 --> 00:02:04.030 align:middle line:84%
his life reviewed and
left his body and so on.

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:06.800 align:middle line:84%
And I was very
impressed by that story,

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:09.789 align:middle line:84%
as all philosophy students
are who read that.

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:13.560 align:middle line:84%
And then three
years later in 1965,

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:16.840 align:middle line:84%
I heard that Dr. George
Ritchie who at that time

00:02:16.840 --> 00:02:20.620 align:middle line:84%
was a professor of psychiatry
at the University of Virginia,

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:23.960 align:middle line:84%
had had such an experience
when he was a young man.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:26.680 align:middle line:84%
And I took that opportunity
to find out and listen

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:28.320 align:middle line:90%
to Dr. Ritchie's story.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.800 align:middle line:84%
I was immediately impressed
by Dr. Ritchie, who

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:34.137 align:middle line:84%
remains the finest
person I ever knew.

00:02:34.137 --> 00:02:35.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, was he's speaking?

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:36.928 align:middle line:84%
Or how did you find
out about his--

00:02:36.928 --> 00:02:39.890 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Dr. Ritchie was very
accessible to the student

00:02:39.890 --> 00:02:43.120 align:middle line:84%
groups around UVA,
and he often lectured.

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:47.960 align:middle line:84%
And so just a short time
after I heard about his story,

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:51.480 align:middle line:84%
I heard him tell it
and was very impressed.

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.080 align:middle line:84%
And since that time, I've
had the wonderful opportunity

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:58.580 align:middle line:84%
and privilege of talking with
literally thousands of people

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:01.710 align:middle line:84%
from all over the world who've
been to the brink of death

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:06.530 align:middle line:84%
but resuscitated and told
these very similar stories.

00:03:06.530 --> 00:03:09.464 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, have you yourself
had a near-death experience

00:03:09.464 --> 00:03:11.880 align:middle line:84%
to be able to write about all
of this, or did you have one

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:14.330 align:middle line:84%
after you started
writing about it all?

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:18.630 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Actually my book
was published in 1975,

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:22.400 align:middle line:84%
and then many years later
I came close to death

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:26.820 align:middle line:84%
by an illness I had called
Hashimoto's disease, which

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:28.610 align:middle line:90%
went undiagnosed.

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:32.330 align:middle line:84%
And in that process I did
come very close to death

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:34.650 align:middle line:90%
and had parts of this.

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.580 align:middle line:84%
You know, not the really
classic, full-blown near-death

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:40.300 align:middle line:84%
experience, but elements
of it, I definitely did.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:42.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you came up
with the characteristics

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:44.820 align:middle line:84%
of a classic
near-death experience

00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:47.140 align:middle line:84%
through the thousands of
people that you've interviewed

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:50.320 align:middle line:84%
and spoken to and listened
to about their experience?

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:54.130 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yes, when "Life After
Life" was written in 1974

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:56.390 align:middle line:84%
and published the year
later, at that time

00:03:56.390 --> 00:03:57.765 align:middle line:84%
I had interviewed
about a hundred

00:03:57.765 --> 00:04:01.960 align:middle line:84%
and-- or knew about
150 cases of this

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:03.990 align:middle line:90%
that I'd been told of by people.

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:07.150 align:middle line:84%
And then of those,
I had interviewed

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:08.930 align:middle line:90%
in depth 50 of them.

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:11.190 align:middle line:84%
And that's how I
came up with the list

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:13.650 align:middle line:84%
of the characteristics,
which incidentally

00:04:13.650 --> 00:04:15.480 align:middle line:90%
has held up very well, because--

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:16.646 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, phenomally, yes.

00:04:16.646 --> 00:04:19.769 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: --this has now been
researched by physicians

00:04:19.769 --> 00:04:24.030 align:middle line:84%
literally on every
continent except Antarctica.

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:28.550 align:middle line:84%
But this a pattern that holds up
pretty much all over the world.

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:30.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's where I connected.

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:33.520 align:middle line:84%
I took a course from you at
the University of Philosophical

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:36.040 align:middle line:84%
Research when I as going
through my Masters.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.410 align:middle line:84%
And I learned about the
near-death experience

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:41.750 align:middle line:84%
through the information
I learned in your course.

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:44.390 align:middle line:90%
Now, I have been through this.

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:46.060 align:middle line:90%
I had a near-death experience.

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:47.790 align:middle line:90%
I had an incredible experience.

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:49.980 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't know
what I went through

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:52.330 align:middle line:90%
until I read it on the internet.

00:04:52.330 --> 00:04:56.770 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, this
didn't only happen to me?

00:04:56.770 --> 00:05:01.960 align:middle line:84%
This is something
that's-- first, for me,

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:05.170 align:middle line:84%
I had the opportunity of
understanding what I went

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:08.290 align:middle line:84%
through, and that it was
not just exclusive to me,

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:10.810 align:middle line:84%
that there's a community of
people where this is also

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:13.250 align:middle line:84%
an experience, and that
this was something.

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:15.570 align:middle line:84%
And I've battled in
my mind for so long.

00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:16.680 align:middle line:90%
Was it psychosomatic?

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:17.641 align:middle line:90%
Was it physiological?

00:05:17.641 --> 00:05:19.890 align:middle line:84%
Is this something that the
consciousness goes through,

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:21.620 align:middle line:90%
that tunnel?

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.300 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure you've addressed
those issues, but--

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:26.170 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, I've
talked with thousands

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:27.740 align:middle line:90%
of people such as yourself.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:31.400 align:middle line:84%
And as a general
rule, what they tell

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:36.190 align:middle line:84%
me is that it was even more
real than ordinary waking

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:36.896 align:middle line:90%
experience.

00:05:36.896 --> 00:05:37.584 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: True.

00:05:37.584 --> 00:05:38.750 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: They say it's not--

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:40.083 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, hyperconsciousness.

00:05:40.083 --> 00:05:41.530 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: --dreamlike in any way.

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:44.260 align:middle line:84%
It's more real than real
is what I've often heard.

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:45.020 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's true.

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:47.360 align:middle line:90%
It's absolutely true.

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:50.040 align:middle line:84%
I was in an accident,
and I had that experience

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:52.070 align:middle line:90%
of lifting up over the scene.

00:05:52.070 --> 00:05:55.150 align:middle line:84%
And I was able to see and hear
the thoughts and the feelings

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:59.120 align:middle line:84%
of all of the medics below
me-- this person, where they're

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:00.610 align:middle line:84%
off purpose, and
this one who had

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:01.818 align:middle line:90%
a problem with relationships.

00:06:01.818 --> 00:06:05.390 align:middle line:84%
I was able to hear
their mind chatter.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:10.670 align:middle line:84%
And at that same time, I was
completely consciously aware

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:14.530 align:middle line:84%
of everything that was going on
in my body, but I wasn't there.

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:17.000 align:middle line:84%
And I'm sure you've heard
this thousands of times.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.640 align:middle line:84%
We actually have
a clip of a movie

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:21.715 align:middle line:84%
that you were in--
it's a great movie.

00:06:21.715 --> 00:06:26.917 align:middle line:84%
And it was called "Through
the Tunnel and Beyond."

00:06:26.917 --> 00:06:29.500 align:middle line:84%
And so I want to show this clip
so that people can kind of get

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:31.570 align:middle line:84%
an idea of what it is
that we're talking about.

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:33.384 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:06:33.384 --> 00:06:34.050 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:35.550 align:middle line:84%
>>DIANNE ARCANGEL:
In helping people

00:06:35.550 --> 00:06:38.470 align:middle line:84%
walk through the grief
process and knowing

00:06:38.470 --> 00:06:40.870 align:middle line:84%
that there is life after
death is tremendously

00:06:40.870 --> 00:06:42.330 align:middle line:90%
healing for them.

00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:45.770 align:middle line:84%
Actually, in my work, I've never
worked with a dying patient who

00:06:45.770 --> 00:06:47.910 align:middle line:84%
did not have an
apparitional experience.

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:48.880 align:middle line:90%
It's 100%.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:50.470 align:middle line:90%
You can write this in stone.

00:06:50.470 --> 00:06:53.449 align:middle line:84%
If a person is terminally ill,
one that's close to death,

00:06:53.449 --> 00:06:55.490 align:middle line:84%
they're going to have an
apparitional experience.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:58.600 align:middle line:90%


00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:01.240 align:middle line:84%
In fact, one thing that
we're doing in hospice,

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:03.235 align:middle line:84%
if a person has had an
apparitional experience

00:07:03.235 --> 00:07:05.890 align:middle line:84%
or if they've had a
reunion, that person becomes

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:07.667 align:middle line:84%
top priority,
because we know death

00:07:07.667 --> 00:07:11.270 align:middle line:84%
is imminent, that it's always
within one week or two weeks

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:12.520 align:middle line:90%
that a person is going to die.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:13.047 align:middle line:90%
No matter.

00:07:13.047 --> 00:07:14.755 align:middle line:84%
If we think maybe
they've got six months,

00:07:14.755 --> 00:07:17.880 align:middle line:84%
we're not real sure if hospice
even ought to take them in,

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:20.280 align:middle line:84%
but once a person has that
apparitional experience,

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:22.320 align:middle line:84%
if they have a
terminal illness, we

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:25.420 align:middle line:84%
know that person is greeting
them, they're loving them,

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:29.047 align:middle line:84%
and they're escalating
them to the other side.

00:07:29.047 --> 00:07:30.630 align:middle line:84%
And then people in
bereavement groups,

00:07:30.630 --> 00:07:34.400 align:middle line:84%
there's a high number
who also have a reunion.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:35.650 align:middle line:90%
I was very familiar with this.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:37.860 align:middle line:84%
It was like a common,
everyday occurrence.

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:39.840 align:middle line:84%
And hearing Dr. Moody
speak for the first time,

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:42.150 align:middle line:90%
I was on the edge of my seat.

00:07:42.150 --> 00:07:45.300 align:middle line:84%
I said, how could he do this
under controlled circumstances?

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:48.520 align:middle line:84%
It was just incredible to me the
thought that he could do that.

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:55.230 align:middle line:84%
62 people have been through
the oracle in Houston.

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:59.480 align:middle line:84%
Out of the 62, 48 have had some
type of reunion experience.

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:03.930 align:middle line:84%
And actually I call mine oracle,
because oracle means a place

00:08:03.930 --> 00:08:05.780 align:middle line:90%
for acquiring wisdom.

00:08:05.780 --> 00:08:10.140 align:middle line:84%
And I have found that even
when a person comes and has

00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:15.060 align:middle line:84%
a session, even if they do not
have a reunion, something very

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:19.125 align:middle line:84%
profound, a deep psychological--
a deep psychic change

00:08:19.125 --> 00:08:21.065 align:middle line:90%
takes place for them.

00:08:21.065 --> 00:08:22.040 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:23.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's so
healing for people

00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:25.310 align:middle line:90%
to go through things like that.

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:28.030 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to talk in a
minute about those controlled

00:08:28.030 --> 00:08:30.040 align:middle line:84%
experiences and how
someone who maybe hasn't

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:34.384 align:middle line:84%
had a near-death experience
can recreate it, in a sense.

00:08:34.384 --> 00:08:36.425 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk a little
about the characteristics

00:08:36.425 --> 00:08:39.480 align:middle line:84%
that you so
wonderfully describe.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:42.370 align:middle line:84%
What is the first experience
that someone typically

00:08:42.370 --> 00:08:45.879 align:middle line:84%
will tell you when they have
this near-death experience?

00:08:45.879 --> 00:08:47.420 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Again,
generally what people

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:52.760 align:middle line:84%
tell us is that when they're
at the brink of death

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:55.550 align:middle line:84%
and their heart stops beating,
for example, that they will

00:08:55.550 --> 00:08:57.830 align:middle line:84%
actually hear the doctor
say something like,

00:08:57.830 --> 00:09:00.150 align:middle line:84%
oh my god, he's dead,
or whatever, which

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.620 align:middle line:84%
comes as a surprise to
them, because what people

00:09:02.620 --> 00:09:05.710 align:middle line:84%
tell me is that--
people say things like,

00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:08.000 align:middle line:84%
I have never felt
so alive as when

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.984 align:middle line:84%
I heard that doctor
say I was dead.

00:09:10.984 --> 00:09:12.400 align:middle line:84%
But from their
point of view, they

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:13.920 align:middle line:90%
seem to leave their bodies.

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:18.090 align:middle line:84%
They watch the scene of the
resuscitation from above.

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:21.490 align:middle line:84%
They can talk about
the conversations that

00:09:21.490 --> 00:09:25.170 align:middle line:84%
went on among the
caretakers and so on,

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:28.630 align:middle line:84%
as you said, not
hearing an audible voice

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:32.630 align:middle line:84%
but rather becoming aware of
the thoughts of the doctors

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:34.087 align:middle line:90%
and nurses and so on.

00:09:34.087 --> 00:09:35.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, as a
psychiatrist though,

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:43.120 align:middle line:84%
is that a normal physiological
response to being unconscious?

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:44.370 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Well, no.

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:46.880 align:middle line:84%
I think that
out-of-body experiences

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:51.090 align:middle line:84%
are-- it's a vast
subject, but no.

00:09:51.090 --> 00:09:54.960 align:middle line:84%
This is something outside of
the realm of psychopathology.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:58.710 align:middle line:84%
This is not anything to
do with mental illness.

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:03.390 align:middle line:84%
But it's an entirely
different category

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:06.260 align:middle line:90%
of altered consciousness.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:08.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, I thought
you as a scientist would

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:11.139 align:middle line:84%
know the differences,
and I've always

00:10:11.139 --> 00:10:12.430 align:middle line:90%
been curious about that myself.

00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:15.310 align:middle line:84%
OK, so someone has this
experience of rising above.

00:10:15.310 --> 00:10:18.050 align:middle line:84%
You hear this time
after time after time.

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:20.780 align:middle line:84%
And then what is
the next experience

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:22.490 align:middle line:90%
that classically follows that?

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:25.420 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Again, what we hear
from people universally,

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:29.660 align:middle line:84%
however articulate or well
educated or multilingual they

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:32.650 align:middle line:84%
may be, they tell
us that they simply

00:10:32.650 --> 00:10:36.460 align:middle line:84%
have no words to describe
what happens next.

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.960 align:middle line:84%
They say this is beyond our
ability to put it into words.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:44.460 align:middle line:84%
But in trying to do
this, what they say

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:48.530 align:middle line:84%
is that they become aware
of a passageway or a tunnel.

00:10:48.530 --> 00:10:50.840 align:middle line:84%
And they go through this
tunnel, and they come out

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:54.730 align:middle line:84%
on the other side into
this incredibly brilliant

00:10:54.730 --> 00:10:58.950 align:middle line:84%
and warm and comforting
and loving light.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:01.720 align:middle line:84%
They seem to be just
taken up in this light.

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:05.570 align:middle line:84%
And in that light, they say that
relatives or friends of theirs

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:07.840 align:middle line:84%
who have already died
seem to be there almost

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:09.860 align:middle line:84%
in the role of a
greeting committee

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:12.230 align:middle line:84%
to help them through
this transition.

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:14.790 align:middle line:84%
And they tell us
about panoramic memory

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:17.640 align:middle line:84%
in which every
detail of their life

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.130 align:middle line:84%
is displayed around
them in this sort

00:11:20.130 --> 00:11:24.566 align:middle line:84%
of full-color,
holographic, 3D panorama.

00:11:24.566 --> 00:11:25.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Like a life review?

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:26.540 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes.

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:29.520 align:middle line:84%
And they say that when you--
in this situation, when

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:32.060 align:middle line:84%
you see each action
of your life,

00:11:32.060 --> 00:11:35.900 align:middle line:84%
it's like you're watching
another person when you see

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:40.370 align:middle line:84%
yourself do that, and that when
the action has its consequence,

00:11:40.370 --> 00:11:43.340 align:middle line:84%
then you are embedded in the
consciousness of the person

00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:45.090 align:middle line:90%
with whom you've interacted.

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:48.520 align:middle line:84%
So if you see yourself doing
something mean to somebody,

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:49.810 align:middle line:90%
then you feel the hurt.

00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:52.880 align:middle line:84%
But if you see yourself
doing something kind hearted,

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:55.700 align:middle line:84%
then you feel the good
feelings you brought about.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:56.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:11:56.650 --> 00:12:01.170 align:middle line:84%
I felt complete expansiveness
of consciousness,

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:04.790 align:middle line:84%
like the walls that
we're in, called

00:12:04.790 --> 00:12:08.650 align:middle line:84%
our body, are
basically limiting,

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:14.150 align:middle line:84%
and what is beyond that is
limitless, is expansive.

00:12:14.150 --> 00:12:19.960 align:middle line:84%
And I somehow found myself with
Asia, that Asia came to me.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:21.470 align:middle line:90%
And that was the limitness.

00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:23.610 align:middle line:90%
That was the-- yeah.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:25.800 align:middle line:84%
Look, I'm trying to put it
into words, and I can't.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:26.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:26.470 --> 00:12:29.180 align:middle line:84%
It was incredible,
expansive consciousness.

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:30.120 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes.

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.600 align:middle line:84%
People say sometimes that
they leave their body

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:37.020 align:middle line:84%
and they go to vast distances
away from the hospital.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:38.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:40.494 align:middle line:84%
We have another clip
from this movie kind

00:12:40.494 --> 00:12:42.910 align:middle line:84%
of explaining or showing this
in a little bit more detail.

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:44.624 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look at that.

00:12:44.624 --> 00:12:48.114 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:48.114 --> 00:12:49.780 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Pretty much
all over the world,

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:53.040 align:middle line:90%
we've found this common pattern.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:56.370 align:middle line:84%
They tell us that at this
point where their doctor says

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:59.260 align:middle line:84%
they are dead, that
they may actually

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:02.740 align:middle line:84%
hear the physician
say, oh my, he's dead,

00:13:02.740 --> 00:13:05.620 align:middle line:84%
or we've lost her, or
something like that.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:07.800 align:middle line:84%
And they say that from
their perspective, actually,

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.620 align:middle line:90%
they still feel very much alive.

00:13:09.620 --> 00:13:12.340 align:middle line:84%
Indeed, their consciousness
is heightened.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.980 align:middle line:84%
And they tell us that they seem
to leave their physical bodies.

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:18.640 align:middle line:84%
They say that they
float up, typically

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:22.620 align:middle line:84%
right above the bed in the
operating room or the emergency

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:23.120 align:middle line:90%
room.

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:26.920 align:middle line:84%
And they look down, and they can
see their own physical bodies

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:28.570 align:middle line:90%
lying on the bed down below.

00:13:28.570 --> 00:13:29.680 align:middle line:90%
>>I was above my body.

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:30.622 align:middle line:90%
I was floating.

00:13:30.622 --> 00:13:32.330 align:middle line:84%
And there were people
around me, except I

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:36.450 align:middle line:84%
didn't realize that that
person there was me.

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:37.640 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:40.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's fascinating
to see that there are so

00:13:40.430 --> 00:13:42.660 align:middle line:84%
many different people
with the same account.

00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:44.535 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes,
all over the world.

00:13:44.535 --> 00:13:45.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All over the world.

00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:47.680 align:middle line:84%
And they just attracted
to you once they

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:49.230 align:middle line:90%
saw this information come out.

00:13:49.230 --> 00:13:53.300 align:middle line:84%
Now, does this have any
type of religious reaction

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:56.440 align:middle line:84%
that you've experienced
in the past?

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:58.370 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, in
terms of people

00:13:58.370 --> 00:14:01.810 align:middle line:84%
who have these experiences,
some were religious

00:14:01.810 --> 00:14:02.627 align:middle line:90%
and some were not.

00:14:02.627 --> 00:14:03.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:14:03.210 --> 00:14:06.880 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: So it doesn't--
whether or not a person has such

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:09.520 align:middle line:84%
an experience doesn't seem
to have anything to do with

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:10.720 align:middle line:90%
whether they were religious.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:12.428 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So does it
depend on their belief

00:14:12.428 --> 00:14:13.450 align:middle line:90%
system ahead of time?

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:15.250 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: I don't think so.

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:18.750 align:middle line:84%
To a certain extent, the
words that they bring to it

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:23.890 align:middle line:84%
have to-- are drawn the
best-- from their traditions,

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:26.890 align:middle line:84%
but this comes with the
proviso that they tell us

00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:29.510 align:middle line:84%
that the words really
aren't adequate.

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:32.750 align:middle line:84%
But one thing we
find is that even

00:14:32.750 --> 00:14:35.970 align:middle line:84%
the people who had no prior
religious understanding

00:14:35.970 --> 00:14:39.020 align:middle line:84%
or belief prior to
this experience,

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:42.100 align:middle line:84%
afterward they come back
and say, wow, it's real.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:42.920 align:middle line:90%
There is a God.

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:45.600 align:middle line:84%
There is life after
death, and so on.

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:50.240 align:middle line:84%
And yet what it tends to do is
to, as a general rule, again,

00:14:50.240 --> 00:14:52.580 align:middle line:90%
to make them nondenominational.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:54.650 align:middle line:84%
What people-- I hear
from people all the time

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:57.690 align:middle line:84%
is they say, well,
you know, what

00:14:57.690 --> 00:15:00.850 align:middle line:84%
I learned was that it
seems to me that all

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:05.150 align:middle line:84%
of the great religions are
looking at part of this,

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:11.190 align:middle line:84%
but that even then that it's
something that transcends even

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:13.980 align:middle line:84%
what the religious
traditions tell us

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:16.720 align:middle line:90%
because it is indescribable.

00:15:16.720 --> 00:15:19.460 align:middle line:84%
People say that it's
beyond their ability

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:20.830 align:middle line:90%
to put it into words.

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:22.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: When you
had your experience,

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:25.480 align:middle line:90%
did you see that light?

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:28.499 align:middle line:84%
Did you go through the
same euphoric experience?

00:15:28.499 --> 00:15:30.540 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, one thing
I should so say probably

00:15:30.540 --> 00:15:34.589 align:middle line:84%
is that not everybody has
this whole full-blown picture.

00:15:34.589 --> 00:15:35.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I'm glad you said that.

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:36.379 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:36.379 --> 00:15:39.890 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: And what it tends to
be is that if somebody has only

00:15:39.890 --> 00:15:42.850 align:middle line:84%
a momentary cardiac
arrest, for example,

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.730 align:middle line:84%
they're more likely to just tell
us one or two of these things,

00:15:45.730 --> 00:15:49.160 align:middle line:84%
like I got out of my body, I
saw the resuscitation going on,

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:51.320 align:middle line:90%
and then I came back to my body.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:54.590 align:middle line:84%
But if the cardiac
arrest, say, ling--

00:15:54.590 --> 00:15:57.360 align:middle line:84%
goes on for several
minutes, then they're

00:15:57.360 --> 00:15:59.940 align:middle line:84%
more likely to tell you more
of the story, like I got out

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:02.820 align:middle line:84%
of my body and went through
this tunnel into the light,

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:03.570 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:16:03.570 --> 00:16:06.970 align:middle line:84%
And in those cases
where the cardiac arrest

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:10.430 align:middle line:84%
go on for extreme
lengths of time,

00:16:10.430 --> 00:16:13.650 align:middle line:84%
people will tell you this
whole full-blown picture

00:16:13.650 --> 00:16:16.570 align:middle line:84%
of going into this light,
and seeing their life

00:16:16.570 --> 00:16:20.450 align:middle line:84%
review, and other
things, as well.

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So it seems to be partly
dependent on how close they

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:24.910 align:middle line:90%
got to death.

00:16:24.910 --> 00:16:28.540 align:middle line:84%
The closer you get to
death, the more involved

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:32.766 align:middle line:84%
and detailed and complex
this experience gets.

00:16:32.766 --> 00:16:34.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How does
this help people

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:37.840 align:middle line:84%
who have people that
they know that have

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:39.340 align:middle line:90%
been through this experience?

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:43.340 align:middle line:84%
How does it help
people deal with death?

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:46.590 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, first of
all, people that come back

00:16:46.590 --> 00:16:50.640 align:middle line:84%
from this experience say
they are not afraid of death,

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:55.870 align:middle line:84%
and that-- because what they
learned from this experience,

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:59.580 align:middle line:84%
it convinces them totally that
what we call death is just

00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:03.100 align:middle line:84%
a transition into another
dimension of existence.

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:05.540 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that it's
a very nice existence.

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:06.990 align:middle line:84%
Have you heard
that consistently?

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:08.244 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes, yes, yes.

00:17:08.244 --> 00:17:09.619 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's very,
very peaceful.

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:10.800 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes, yes.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:16.111 align:middle line:84%
And so they say that-- and
completely wrapped up in love

00:17:16.111 --> 00:17:17.319 align:middle line:90%
is what you hear from people.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:18.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:17:18.230 --> 00:17:19.089 align:middle line:90%
Unconditional.

00:17:19.089 --> 00:17:19.819 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes.

00:17:19.819 --> 00:17:21.760 align:middle line:84%
And yet at the
same time, they say

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:25.950 align:middle line:84%
that it's not that they
want to die anytime soon,

00:17:25.950 --> 00:17:30.310 align:middle line:84%
that they realize that life
is a learning experience,

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:34.780 align:middle line:84%
and that certainly it's a
bad move to take yourself out

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:39.220 align:middle line:84%
of it prematurely, but that
life has a purpose, too.

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:41.880 align:middle line:84%
And yet at the same
time, Lisa, there

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:47.310 align:middle line:84%
is this universal thing I
hear so often from people

00:17:47.310 --> 00:17:50.570 align:middle line:84%
that there's always
a kind of nostalgia.

00:17:50.570 --> 00:17:53.120 align:middle line:90%


00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:55.150 align:middle line:84%
Dr. George Ritchie,
the first person

00:17:55.150 --> 00:17:57.660 align:middle line:84%
I-- living person I
ever heard this from,

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:01.460 align:middle line:84%
used to say that sometimes
he just got homesick

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:04.250 align:middle line:84%
for that beautiful
place he had been,

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:06.630 align:middle line:84%
and that many times in
working with patients,

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:12.770 align:middle line:84%
for example, he felt
this presence of love

00:18:12.770 --> 00:18:14.670 align:middle line:84%
that he had
encountered and so on.

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:19.090 align:middle line:84%
So there's that homesickness,
too, and yet this willingness

00:18:19.090 --> 00:18:23.180 align:middle line:84%
and commitment to go on in life
and to get things done here,

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:23.680 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:24.179 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:18:24.179 --> 00:18:25.480 align:middle line:90%
I absolutely experienced that.

00:18:25.480 --> 00:18:27.780 align:middle line:84%
That's when I started my
radio show and everything.

00:18:27.780 --> 00:18:30.160 align:middle line:84%
But when people
come to you and they

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:34.360 align:middle line:84%
explain their circumstances,
their experiences with this,

00:18:34.360 --> 00:18:36.860 align:middle line:90%
do you counsel them?

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:38.570 align:middle line:84%
What do you say to
them, and how do you

00:18:38.570 --> 00:18:41.222 align:middle line:84%
give them guidance
to continue on?

00:18:41.222 --> 00:18:42.680 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, when
I first started

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:47.160 align:middle line:84%
doing this back in
the '60s, people

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:50.100 align:middle line:84%
who had this experience
very often suspected

00:18:50.100 --> 00:18:51.860 align:middle line:90%
they might be alone.

00:18:51.860 --> 00:18:52.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:18:52.360 --> 00:18:53.160 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:55.410 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: And many people
didn't want to talk about it.

00:18:55.410 --> 00:18:55.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:18:55.850 --> 00:18:56.350 align:middle line:90%
Uh-uh.

00:18:56.350 --> 00:18:57.000 align:middle line:90%
Uh-uh.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: And so it was
a great relief to them

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:03.630 align:middle line:84%
to be able to talk
with somebody who

00:19:03.630 --> 00:19:08.485 align:middle line:84%
was accepting and understood
and had heard this before.

00:19:08.485 --> 00:19:12.804 align:middle line:84%
And I think it does help people
to talk about their experience.

00:19:12.804 --> 00:19:13.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It does.

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:18.520 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: But far more,
I think, is the impact

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:21.800 align:middle line:84%
that the experience has
on these two things.

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:24.470 align:middle line:84%
Number one, that it
eliminates the fear of death.

00:19:24.470 --> 00:19:28.380 align:middle line:84%
And secondly, that whatever
they had been chasing before--

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:31.980 align:middle line:84%
and it's my experience,
both as a human being

00:19:31.980 --> 00:19:34.740 align:middle line:84%
and as a psychiatrist,
is that everybody

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:36.980 align:middle line:90%
seems to be chasing something.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:40.410 align:middle line:84%
Like, I've spent my
life chasing knowledge.

00:19:40.410 --> 00:19:43.650 align:middle line:84%
Some people chase
fame or power or money

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:44.890 align:middle line:90%
or any of these other things.

00:19:44.890 --> 00:19:46.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a pursuit,
constant pursuit.

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:48.060 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: But whatever
they were chasing,

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:52.720 align:middle line:84%
they said when they come back
from this that it's-- what they

00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:57.143 align:middle line:84%
realized that what this is
all about is to learn to love.

00:19:57.143 --> 00:20:00.050 align:middle line:84%
And that even when
they-- Because

00:20:00.050 --> 00:20:03.680 align:middle line:84%
if you think about this review,
then it becomes obvious.

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:06.000 align:middle line:84%
Because they see
in this life review

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.930 align:middle line:84%
that if they've been
unkind to people, then

00:20:08.930 --> 00:20:14.190 align:middle line:84%
at the end of their life, that
they empathically experience

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:17.110 align:middle line:84%
the hurt that they brought
about in other people's lives.

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:19.890 align:middle line:84%
And if they've done
nice things, then they

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:21.010 align:middle line:90%
feel the good feelings.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:26.081 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA:I got to tell you
that I-- I-- I just--

00:20:26.081 --> 00:20:27.580 align:middle line:84%
that is exactly
what happened to me.

00:20:27.580 --> 00:20:32.950 align:middle line:84%
And I'm taking this moment
as just a-- I was broken up

00:20:32.950 --> 00:20:36.580 align:middle line:84%
with my boyfriend
at the time, and he

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:38.460 align:middle line:84%
was the one who was
the first person

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:41.020 align:middle line:90%
at the scene of the accident.

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:42.480 align:middle line:90%
It was a bike accident.

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:47.640 align:middle line:84%
And it was that moment-- it
was after that that I realized

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:49.940 align:middle line:84%
he was the man I was
supposed to marry.

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:50.461 align:middle line:90%
And I did.

00:20:50.461 --> 00:20:52.460 align:middle line:84%
And I married him, and
I'm still married to him.

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:53.460 align:middle line:90%
But that is true.

00:20:53.460 --> 00:20:55.460 align:middle line:84%
It was-- the
relationship was-- it

00:20:55.460 --> 00:20:58.930 align:middle line:84%
was-- I was not good
in the relationship.

00:20:58.930 --> 00:21:01.120 align:middle line:90%
And I got that completely.

00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:04.400 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't intentional that I got
that, that I woke up and went,

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:06.180 align:middle line:90%
oh, I was da--

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.610 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for saying that,
because that is absolutely

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:09.450 align:middle line:90%
what happened to me.

00:21:09.450 --> 00:21:12.760 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I got a full wake-up
call about-- and this

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:15.289 align:middle line:84%
was-- this is the
man I'm supposed

00:21:15.289 --> 00:21:16.580 align:middle line:90%
to be with the rest of my life.

00:21:16.580 --> 00:21:19.380 align:middle line:84%
And I had-- it wasn't
only that experience that

00:21:19.380 --> 00:21:21.199 align:middle line:84%
made me realize that,
but now that you're

00:21:21.199 --> 00:21:22.990 align:middle line:84%
saying this, that is
exactly what happened.

00:21:22.990 --> 00:21:24.540 align:middle line:90%
He helped me back to health.

00:21:24.540 --> 00:21:25.730 align:middle line:84%
He was the one who took
me to the hospital,

00:21:25.730 --> 00:21:27.646 align:middle line:84%
because I couldn't
remember anything, my name.

00:21:27.646 --> 00:21:28.780 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't speak.

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:31.030 align:middle line:90%
And he spoke for me.

00:21:31.030 --> 00:21:31.965 align:middle line:90%
And it was beautiful.

00:21:31.965 --> 00:21:34.250 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, how wonderful.

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:36.690 align:middle line:84%
If you think about this
life review for a moment,

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:38.676 align:middle line:90%
this is a startling thing.

00:21:38.676 --> 00:21:43.530 align:middle line:84%
Let's-- For the moment, let's
set aside all talk about life

00:21:43.530 --> 00:21:48.880 align:middle line:84%
after death, and let's just ask
what we can draw as a minimal

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:50.160 align:middle line:90%
inference.

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:55.450 align:middle line:84%
Let's say we don't-- we want
to draw the smallest inference

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:56.760 align:middle line:90%
that we can.

00:21:56.760 --> 00:21:59.030 align:middle line:84%
We want to-- For the
moment, we'll just set aside

00:21:59.030 --> 00:22:02.380 align:middle line:84%
thinking about life after death,
and we'll think about this one

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:05.620 align:middle line:84%
thing that people,
in their life review,

00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:09.340 align:middle line:84%
see what they have done
to others and the feelings

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:10.490 align:middle line:90%
they brought about.

00:22:10.490 --> 00:22:12.880 align:middle line:84%
Now, just from that
one fact, we can draw,

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:17.140 align:middle line:84%
I think quite confidently,
an amazing conclusion,

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:22.200 align:middle line:84%
which is that life is
a two-phase process.

00:22:22.200 --> 00:22:27.770 align:middle line:84%
Like at first, we
lead it forward,

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:30.370 align:middle line:90%
as the actor or protagonist.

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:33.220 align:middle line:84%
And then, at the end of
death-- at the end of life,

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:36.960 align:middle line:84%
it's like we switch around
and we watch the same action

00:22:36.960 --> 00:22:40.460 align:middle line:84%
from the perspective of
the other characters.

00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:42.960 align:middle line:90%
Now that, to me, is startling.

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:44.700 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Give me an
example of that.

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:46.110 align:middle line:90%
I see what you're saying, but--

00:22:46.110 --> 00:22:55.170 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, for example, if I
do something unkind to someone,

00:22:55.170 --> 00:23:01.740 align:middle line:84%
then when I die I'm
going to be that person.

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:04.330 align:middle line:84%
When I review that
action, I won't see it

00:23:04.330 --> 00:23:05.680 align:middle line:90%
through these eyes.

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:08.580 align:middle line:84%
I will see it through
the heart of the person

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:10.220 align:middle line:90%
with whom I've interacted.

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And what this really
does for you, I think,

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:15.340 align:middle line:84%
is it makes you
much more cautious.

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:17.780 align:middle line:84%
I've tried for many
years to always keep

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:21.450 align:middle line:84%
that in my mind, that
whatever I'm doing or saying

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:24.050 align:middle line:84%
that someday I'm going
to have to look at this

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:26.120 align:middle line:84%
from the other
person's perspective.

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:29.160 align:middle line:84%
Now, I will also
be quite honest.

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:31.990 align:middle line:90%
It works, but it works slowly.

00:23:31.990 --> 00:23:33.580 align:middle line:90%
It takes practice.

00:23:33.580 --> 00:23:39.520 align:middle line:84%
And you still find yourself
flying off the handle or saying

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:41.200 align:middle line:90%
things you wish you hadn't.

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:45.960 align:middle line:84%
But I think when I look back on
my life for the last 40 years,

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:48.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm doing it a greater
and greater percentage

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:49.890 align:middle line:90%
of the time at least.

00:23:49.890 --> 00:23:52.890 align:middle line:84%
But even people who've been
through this experience

00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:56.790 align:middle line:84%
and who've, years ago, will
say that-- as Dr. George

00:23:56.790 --> 00:24:00.650 align:middle line:84%
Ritchie said to me one time-- he
said, Raymond, this experience

00:24:00.650 --> 00:24:05.020 align:middle line:84%
makes your humanity even
more of a burden in a way.

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:08.950 align:middle line:84%
And George was just a very
extremely kind-hearted

00:24:08.950 --> 00:24:10.240 align:middle line:90%
individual.

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:12.769 align:middle line:84%
And he wouldn't have
put it in the words

00:24:12.769 --> 00:24:14.310 align:middle line:84%
that I'm going to
put it in, but I've

00:24:14.310 --> 00:24:16.770 align:middle line:84%
heard that same
sentiment expressed

00:24:16.770 --> 00:24:18.160 align:middle line:90%
from so many other people.

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:22.220 align:middle line:84%
I know exactly what he meant,
and that is, let's face it.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:25.250 align:middle line:84%
It's very difficult to get
through the average day

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:28.690 align:middle line:84%
without wanting to choke
at least one person.

00:24:28.690 --> 00:24:31.340 align:middle line:90%
That's the reality of life.

00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:34.490 align:middle line:84%
And what people say is in
this review of their life,

00:24:34.490 --> 00:24:37.690 align:middle line:84%
they see that what this
is all about is love,

00:24:37.690 --> 00:24:41.310 align:middle line:84%
but that it's still very
difficult on the daily--

00:24:41.310 --> 00:24:44.440 align:middle line:84%
day-to-day routine, that
you find yourself flying off

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:47.600 align:middle line:84%
the handle, but
that gradually, I

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:51.030 align:middle line:84%
think by making
this a practice, you

00:24:51.030 --> 00:24:52.960 align:middle line:90%
do get more conscious of it.

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:54.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I will
assert that you don't

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:57.250 align:middle line:84%
need to even necessarily
have a near-death experience

00:24:57.250 --> 00:24:58.170 align:middle line:90%
to get that lesson.

00:24:58.170 --> 00:24:59.920 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, that's
true, but definitely

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:01.630 align:middle line:84%
a near-death
experience helps that.

00:25:01.630 --> 00:25:04.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It definitely
emphasizes it, yes.

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:07.310 align:middle line:84%
But I would suggest
that's a wonderful way

00:25:07.310 --> 00:25:09.260 align:middle line:84%
to look at living
life is to understand

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:13.805 align:middle line:84%
that in the overall life review,
it is about consciousness,

00:25:13.805 --> 00:25:18.680 align:middle line:84%
it is about love, and it is
about ultimately taking care

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:20.104 align:middle line:90%
of other people.

00:25:20.104 --> 00:25:20.770 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's--

00:25:20.770 --> 00:25:22.100 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: It is.

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:24.474 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Just the-- being
aware of the feelings

00:25:24.474 --> 00:25:25.140 align:middle line:90%
of other people.

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:27.540 align:middle line:84%
Being aware of the feelings
of other people, really.

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:28.450 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes.

00:25:28.450 --> 00:25:31.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, let's get-- so
shared death experiences.

00:25:31.110 --> 00:25:32.910 align:middle line:84%
What are shared
death experiences?

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:37.520 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, a very
interesting fact is that all

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:40.860 align:middle line:84%
of the phenomena
that we identify

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:44.820 align:middle line:84%
as the near-death experience,
including leaving the body,

00:25:44.820 --> 00:25:48.250 align:middle line:84%
going toward this
light, seeing the light,

00:25:48.250 --> 00:25:50.160 align:middle line:84%
seeing the apparitions
of the deceased

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:54.930 align:middle line:84%
and so on, and even the
panoramic life review,

00:25:54.930 --> 00:25:57.860 align:middle line:84%
occur frequently
not just to people

00:25:57.860 --> 00:26:01.700 align:middle line:84%
who almost die and return
but to the bystanders

00:26:01.700 --> 00:26:03.980 align:middle line:90%
at the bedside of the dying.

00:26:03.980 --> 00:26:05.740 align:middle line:84%
That it's a very
frequent phenomenon

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:10.430 align:middle line:84%
that, as someone dies, that
the bystanders themselves

00:26:10.430 --> 00:26:13.030 align:middle line:84%
will have these elements
that we identify

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:14.770 align:middle line:90%
as the near-death experience.

00:26:14.770 --> 00:26:18.390 align:middle line:84%
For example, they may
say that, as mother died,

00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:20.910 align:middle line:84%
I myself felt that
I left my body

00:26:20.910 --> 00:26:24.370 align:middle line:84%
and accompanied her
partway toward this light.

00:26:24.370 --> 00:26:27.190 align:middle line:84%
Or you hear a lot of people,
including-- I hear this a lot

00:26:27.190 --> 00:26:30.010 align:middle line:84%
from doctors, that
as the patient died,

00:26:30.010 --> 00:26:34.250 align:middle line:84%
they saw what seemed to be
a light leave from typically

00:26:34.250 --> 00:26:36.680 align:middle line:84%
the upper part of
the body and rise up,

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:41.000 align:middle line:84%
or in some cases a transparent
replica of the person stand up

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.920 align:middle line:90%
and move away from the body.

00:26:43.920 --> 00:26:48.340 align:middle line:84%
And hearing music at the bedside
of the dying is very common,

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:50.830 align:middle line:84%
or how the light
permeates everything.

00:26:50.830 --> 00:26:53.340 align:middle line:84%
And the bystanders
may say that they

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:57.460 align:middle line:84%
see the spirits of
the deceased relatives

00:26:57.460 --> 00:27:02.210 align:middle line:84%
and loved ones of the person
who's dying come into the room

00:27:02.210 --> 00:27:04.310 align:middle line:90%
as to escort them away.

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:08.840 align:middle line:84%
And most incredibly,
and I have many cases

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:12.000 align:middle line:84%
of interviewed over the
years of people who tell me

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:17.020 align:middle line:84%
that, as their loved one died,
they empathically co-lived

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:21.700 align:middle line:84%
the life review of the
person who passed away.

00:27:21.700 --> 00:27:22.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:25.990 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Now, what the
shared death experiences mean

00:27:25.990 --> 00:27:31.110 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the typical
way that this is debated

00:27:31.110 --> 00:27:33.040 align:middle line:84%
is that-- well, I'm
sure that everybody's

00:27:33.040 --> 00:27:35.950 align:middle line:84%
heard that when the
discussion turns

00:27:35.950 --> 00:27:39.350 align:middle line:84%
to near-death experiences,
some people take it seriously.

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:41.600 align:middle line:84%
Other people say,
well, this is just

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:44.470 align:middle line:84%
the cutoff of the oxygen
flow to the brain,

00:27:44.470 --> 00:27:47.130 align:middle line:84%
creates this
hallucinatory phenomenon

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:49.830 align:middle line:84%
that gets reported as the
near-death experience.

00:27:49.830 --> 00:27:54.490 align:middle line:84%
But that fails to account for
why the bystanders would have

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:58.610 align:middle line:84%
the same experience, because
the oxygen flow to their brain

00:27:58.610 --> 00:28:01.915 align:middle line:84%
is not compromised and yet
they have the same experience.

00:28:01.915 --> 00:28:04.507 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you've heard this
over and over and over again?

00:28:04.507 --> 00:28:05.090 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yeah.

00:28:05.090 --> 00:28:10.710 align:middle line:84%
Initially from one of my own
medical professors back in 1972

00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:12.630 align:middle line:84%
who had such an
experience when she

00:28:12.630 --> 00:28:17.660 align:middle line:84%
was trying to resuscitate her
own mother who passed away.

00:28:17.660 --> 00:28:20.020 align:middle line:84%
And when her mother did
pass away, the physician

00:28:20.020 --> 00:28:23.990 align:middle line:84%
herself left her body and
went partway toward this light

00:28:23.990 --> 00:28:26.370 align:middle line:90%
with her mother who was dying.

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:27.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness.

00:28:27.490 --> 00:28:30.680 align:middle line:84%
Your experiences
have been incredible.

00:28:30.680 --> 00:28:34.210 align:middle line:84%
So this took you on a
journey to various locations

00:28:34.210 --> 00:28:36.990 align:middle line:90%
around our world.

00:28:36.990 --> 00:28:39.180 align:middle line:90%
We have a clip of a place.

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:41.720 align:middle line:84%
Tell us a little bit about
what we're going to see here.

00:28:41.720 --> 00:28:42.428 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes.

00:28:42.428 --> 00:28:46.520 align:middle line:84%
Well, incredible as it may
seem, the factual reality,

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:50.120 align:middle line:84%
which you can learn
from standard textbooks

00:28:50.120 --> 00:28:52.730 align:middle line:84%
of ancient Greek
philosophy, for example,

00:28:52.730 --> 00:28:55.320 align:middle line:84%
is that the ancient
Greek philosophers,

00:28:55.320 --> 00:28:59.050 align:middle line:84%
who are the foundation stones
of all Western civilization--

00:28:59.050 --> 00:29:00.840 align:middle line:90%
that's where it began.

00:29:00.840 --> 00:29:05.500 align:middle line:84%
But these individuals, many
of them during their lifetimes

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:08.670 align:middle line:84%
were thought to
have been related

00:29:08.670 --> 00:29:14.950 align:middle line:84%
to this technique of calling
up the spirits of the deceased.

00:29:14.950 --> 00:29:17.955 align:middle line:84%
And the ancient Greeks
had institutions

00:29:17.955 --> 00:29:21.730 align:middle line:84%
where they-- which they
called Oracles of the Dead,

00:29:21.730 --> 00:29:26.600 align:middle line:84%
where they practiced various
procedures to be able to bring

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:29.480 align:middle line:84%
people into a state of
consciousness during which they

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:34.160 align:middle line:84%
would have visionary reunions
with their departed loved ones.

00:29:34.160 --> 00:29:36.870 align:middle line:84%
Well, I was interested
in this in college,

00:29:36.870 --> 00:29:42.060 align:middle line:84%
but back in the 1980s I read
the archaeological reports

00:29:42.060 --> 00:29:45.030 align:middle line:84%
where one of these sites
had been uncovered.

00:29:45.030 --> 00:29:47.950 align:middle line:84%
And based on what the
archaeologists found,

00:29:47.950 --> 00:29:50.340 align:middle line:84%
I was able to figure
out how they did it.

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:54.180 align:middle line:84%
And so I set it
up, and it works.

00:29:54.180 --> 00:29:56.310 align:middle line:90%
And now I-- It works.

00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:58.700 align:middle line:84%
And then you might
say, well, sure,

00:29:58.700 --> 00:30:00.350 align:middle line:90%
it works for Raymond Moody.

00:30:00.350 --> 00:30:03.710 align:middle line:84%
No, it works for anybody
who wants to set it up.

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:08.610 align:middle line:84%
And numerous other psychologists
and so on around the world

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:15.930 align:middle line:84%
have set up this procedure and
apparatus that I figured out.

00:30:15.930 --> 00:30:17.320 align:middle line:90%
And it really does work.

00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:21.620 align:middle line:84%
You can take people through
a procedure during which,

00:30:21.620 --> 00:30:24.240 align:middle line:84%
in a full state of
waking awareness,

00:30:24.240 --> 00:30:27.600 align:middle line:84%
they seem to see and
converse with the spirits

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:29.094 align:middle line:90%
of their departed loved ones.

00:30:29.094 --> 00:30:31.260 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's more of a
journey that they go through,

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:32.890 align:middle line:84%
and it's based on
what you found.

00:30:32.890 --> 00:30:35.990 align:middle line:84%
I want to show people the
clip of where you were.

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.560 align:middle line:84%
This is basically
the place in Greece,

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:41.120 align:middle line:84%
which is the origin of
the Oracle of the Dead.

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:43.546 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look at this.

00:30:43.546 --> 00:30:44.450 align:middle line:90%
