Dakaris in his search

00:30:48.330 --> 00:30:54.400 align:middle line:84%
for this site surmised that,
in fact, the Oracle was

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:58.500 align:middle line:84%
in the northwest corner
of Greece in Epirus.

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:03.630 align:middle line:84%
Homer talks about the Oracle
being located at a point

00:31:03.630 --> 00:31:08.270 align:middle line:84%
where two rivers flow together
to form the Acheron River

00:31:08.270 --> 00:31:11.470 align:middle line:84%
and that there was
a pinnacle of rock.

00:31:11.470 --> 00:31:16.375 align:middle line:84%
All Dr. Dakaris did was to trust
Homer and to go to the location

00:31:16.375 --> 00:31:19.320 align:middle line:84%
that he believed Homer
was talking about,

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:26.450 align:middle line:84%
excavate it, and indeed did find
this subterranean complex there

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:32.690 align:middle line:84%
exactly at the location where he
surmised Homer had located it.

00:31:32.690 --> 00:31:35.990 align:middle line:84%
The institution
was subterranean.

00:31:35.990 --> 00:31:41.460 align:middle line:84%
This was another factor in why
it was so long undiscovered.

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:47.390 align:middle line:84%
Even in its heyday in antiquity,
it was entirely underground.

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:51.480 align:middle line:84%
In approximately
160 BC, the Romans

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:54.370 align:middle line:90%
burned the Oracle of the Dead.

00:31:54.370 --> 00:32:02.360 align:middle line:84%
And at this point, this dropped
out of Western civilization

00:32:02.360 --> 00:32:03.460 align:middle line:90%
as we know it.

00:32:03.460 --> 00:32:08.270 align:middle line:84%
Then subsequently in about
350 AD, the church banned it.

00:32:08.270 --> 00:32:10.590 align:middle line:84%
They made it anathema
for a Christian

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:14.220 align:middle line:84%
to believe that a spirit
can be seen in the mirror.

00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:17.420 align:middle line:84%
And so for that reason, we have
had no continuing tradition

00:32:17.420 --> 00:32:22.130 align:middle line:84%
of evocation of the deceased
in Western civilization.

00:32:22.130 --> 00:32:26.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you went to this
location with the idea in mind

00:32:26.870 --> 00:32:30.120 align:middle line:84%
to be able to
replicate this concept

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:32.060 align:middle line:90%
of the Oracle of the Dead?

00:32:32.060 --> 00:32:33.630 align:middle line:90%
And so you explored it.

00:32:33.630 --> 00:32:36.660 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yes, and you don't
really need much equipment.

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:39.040 align:middle line:84%
This worked by
creating what we called

00:32:39.040 --> 00:32:43.480 align:middle line:84%
an optical clear depth, where
you can take a polished silver

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:47.070 align:middle line:84%
bowl, for example, fill it
with water and olive oil.

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:50.480 align:middle line:84%
And you gaze into it, and
that gives you a depth.

00:32:50.480 --> 00:32:52.730 align:middle line:84%
You don't see any
reflections, but just

00:32:52.730 --> 00:32:55.360 align:middle line:84%
like you're gazing
away into eternity.

00:32:55.360 --> 00:32:58.170 align:middle line:84%
And under that
circumstance, many people

00:32:58.170 --> 00:33:02.380 align:middle line:84%
will have what we call eidetic
imagery, which is full-color,

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:08.020 align:middle line:84%
moving, three-dimensional,
brightly colored visions

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:11.250 align:middle line:84%
of which you don't seem to have
any conscious control over.

00:33:11.250 --> 00:33:14.020 align:middle line:90%
They unfold of their own accord.

00:33:14.020 --> 00:33:17.690 align:middle line:84%
And so I just set this up
in my research facility

00:33:17.690 --> 00:33:22.250 align:middle line:84%
and just took a big wall
mirror and surrounded it

00:33:22.250 --> 00:33:25.440 align:middle line:84%
in a darkened area
with black cloth

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:30.100 align:middle line:84%
so that you exclude reflections,
got a comfortable easy chair

00:33:30.100 --> 00:33:33.320 align:middle line:84%
in front of it, and you take
people through a procedure.

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:36.380 align:middle line:84%
You ask them to choose
some one person who's

00:33:36.380 --> 00:33:38.600 align:middle line:84%
died that they
want to see again.

00:33:38.600 --> 00:33:41.900 align:middle line:84%
And then just as I would
as a grief counselor,

00:33:41.900 --> 00:33:45.890 align:middle line:84%
I get them to talk
about the person,

00:33:45.890 --> 00:33:48.790 align:middle line:84%
to bring up all their
memories and to talk

00:33:48.790 --> 00:33:51.000 align:middle line:84%
about the good points
of the relationship,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.370 align:middle line:84%
the sticking points
of the relationship.

00:33:53.370 --> 00:33:55.480 align:middle line:90%
This lasts an hour or two.

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:57.850 align:middle line:84%
Then you let them sit
in this little chamber

00:33:57.850 --> 00:34:01.040 align:middle line:84%
and leave them in there
for about an hour,

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:02.745 align:middle line:84%
and tell them just
to get relaxed

00:34:02.745 --> 00:34:04.700 align:middle line:90%
and to gaze into the mirror.

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:09.310 align:middle line:84%
And under those circumstances,
many people actually

00:34:09.310 --> 00:34:13.790 align:middle line:84%
do see full-color, very
lifelike apparitions

00:34:13.790 --> 00:34:16.270 align:middle line:90%
of their departed loved ones.

00:34:16.270 --> 00:34:20.020 align:middle line:84%
About 30% of them tell
us that they absolutely

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.750 align:middle line:84%
hear the audible
voice of the deceased.

00:34:22.750 --> 00:34:25.420 align:middle line:84%
Almost all the rest
of them talk about

00:34:25.420 --> 00:34:31.770 align:middle line:84%
a mind-to-mind or heart-to-heart
communication, a vivid sense

00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:33.383 align:middle line:90%
of the presence of the deceased.

00:34:33.383 --> 00:34:36.870 align:middle line:90%


00:34:36.870 --> 00:34:38.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is this a healing
experience for people?

00:34:38.870 --> 00:34:39.900 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yeah.

00:34:39.900 --> 00:34:43.469 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this does
seem to really help

00:34:43.469 --> 00:34:47.100 align:middle line:90%
people move on in their grief.

00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:49.540 align:middle line:84%
Because one thing
I hear from people

00:34:49.540 --> 00:34:53.880 align:middle line:84%
all the time is that, if I
only had five more minutes.

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:56.600 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
we're able to provide.

00:34:56.600 --> 00:34:58.880 align:middle line:90%
This does work.

00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:03.100 align:middle line:84%
And this is not Raymond
Moody talking, but--

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:05.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You've done this
under scientific studies.

00:35:05.740 --> 00:35:09.300 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, I've done
it under very controlled

00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:10.270 align:middle line:90%
circumstances.

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:19.135 align:middle line:84%
And this is now taught at
a institute in California,

00:35:19.135 --> 00:35:21.550 align:middle line:84%
a psychotherapy
training institute.

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:25.272 align:middle line:84%
It's incorporated into
the curriculum there.

00:35:25.272 --> 00:35:26.105 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:35:26.105 --> 00:35:28.240 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, We're going to show
some pictures of that.

00:35:28.240 --> 00:35:31.350 align:middle line:84%
But it was all based
on your experiences

00:35:31.350 --> 00:35:34.015 align:middle line:84%
of where you went to the
Oracle of the Dead to see.

00:35:34.015 --> 00:35:36.390 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a look at that,
because it shows the ruins.

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:39.300 align:middle line:84%
And this is what they did in the
ancient Greek culture, right?

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:41.610 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes, this
was part and parcel

00:35:41.610 --> 00:35:44.180 align:middle line:84%
of the ancient Greek
culture, and many

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:47.230 align:middle line:84%
of the great classical
writers of antiquity

00:35:47.230 --> 00:35:48.490 align:middle line:90%
talk about this place.

00:35:48.490 --> 00:35:53.160 align:middle line:84%
So it was a standard
institution in ancient Greece.

00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:54.720 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So you had to go.

00:35:54.720 --> 00:35:56.704 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look at it.

00:35:56.704 --> 00:35:58.267 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:35:58.267 --> 00:35:59.850 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY (VOICEOVER):
We're here at one

00:35:59.850 --> 00:36:05.150 align:middle line:84%
of the most amazing places in
the world-- to me, at least.

00:36:05.150 --> 00:36:08.230 align:middle line:84%
This is the Oracle
of the Dead at Ephyra

00:36:08.230 --> 00:36:10.160 align:middle line:84%
where, in ancient
times, people would

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:14.110 align:middle line:84%
come to actually see and
visit with the spirits

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:16.600 align:middle line:90%
of their departed loved ones.

00:36:16.600 --> 00:36:19.030 align:middle line:84%
Until recent times,
scholars have

00:36:19.030 --> 00:36:20.750 align:middle line:84%
assumed that what
was going on here

00:36:20.750 --> 00:36:25.040 align:middle line:84%
was simple fraud, in the sense
that we in the 20th century

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:28.870 align:middle line:84%
West presumably know that such
things that were described here

00:36:28.870 --> 00:36:32.010 align:middle line:90%
by the ancient writers can't be.

00:36:32.010 --> 00:36:34.360 align:middle line:84%
But in light of
recent developments

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:35.920 align:middle line:84%
and research that's
been done now

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:39.060 align:middle line:84%
by many psychologists
replicating

00:36:39.060 --> 00:36:42.290 align:middle line:84%
the experience of seeing
apparitions of the departed,

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:46.020 align:middle line:84%
we can now have a
plausible explanation

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:49.160 align:middle line:84%
for what was going on in this
rather amazing sanctuary.

00:36:49.160 --> 00:36:52.720 align:middle line:90%


00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:57.850 align:middle line:84%
And now we come through this
entranceway of enormous stones

00:36:57.850 --> 00:37:02.790 align:middle line:84%
into a courtyard,
which is laid out

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:05.890 align:middle line:84%
to give the impression
that one is in a cave

00:37:05.890 --> 00:37:07.560 align:middle line:90%
or in an underground world.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:12.480 align:middle line:84%
One has to imagine that in
antiquity this was roofed over

00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:15.580 align:middle line:84%
so that we literally
felt as though we

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:18.400 align:middle line:90%
were in the underworld.

00:37:18.400 --> 00:37:21.070 align:middle line:84%
At this point,
the pilgrims would

00:37:21.070 --> 00:37:25.750 align:middle line:84%
have been met by the
psychagogues, the guides who

00:37:25.750 --> 00:37:27.900 align:middle line:84%
lived here to
conduct the pilgrims

00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:34.990 align:middle line:84%
though the experience of
visiting with their deceased.

00:37:34.990 --> 00:37:38.400 align:middle line:84%
As we go in a little bit
into the more functioning

00:37:38.400 --> 00:37:45.400 align:middle line:84%
part of the Oracle proper, we
find immediately in front of us

00:37:45.400 --> 00:37:47.490 align:middle line:90%
here a wall.

00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:51.390 align:middle line:84%
The right part of the wall
was a medieval addition.

00:37:51.390 --> 00:37:58.790 align:middle line:84%
The Byzantine church built a
chapel here in medieval times

00:37:58.790 --> 00:38:03.310 align:middle line:84%
on the ruins of
the ancient Oracle.

00:38:03.310 --> 00:38:07.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So they did
this 2,300 years ago.

00:38:07.180 --> 00:38:11.220 align:middle line:84%
It shows that people have
been so curious about life

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:16.880 align:middle line:84%
beyond life, or this passing
experience, for so long.

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:20.590 align:middle line:84%
What exactly did
they use that for?

00:38:20.590 --> 00:38:22.710 align:middle line:90%
What was that for?

00:38:22.710 --> 00:38:24.990 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Basically, when
you read the accounts that

00:38:24.990 --> 00:38:27.100 align:middle line:84%
have survived from
antiquity of people

00:38:27.100 --> 00:38:29.850 align:middle line:84%
who visited this
Oracle of the Dead,

00:38:29.850 --> 00:38:31.830 align:middle line:84%
you can pretty much
tell that basically

00:38:31.830 --> 00:38:34.420 align:middle line:90%
what it was was grief.

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.610 align:middle line:84%
This was a way that
they had if they

00:38:36.610 --> 00:38:40.720 align:middle line:84%
had some issue with the
person who had passed away

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:42.380 align:middle line:90%
that they couldn't get beyond.

00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:45.360 align:middle line:84%
They would go to these places
and go through this procedure,

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:48.630 align:middle line:84%
during which they could
actually see and converse

00:38:48.630 --> 00:38:51.770 align:middle line:90%
with the person and clear it up.

00:38:51.770 --> 00:38:53.360 align:middle line:84%
And that's the
same reason people

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:55.757 align:middle line:90%
have come to me at my place.

00:38:55.757 --> 00:38:57.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: For thousands
of years, people

00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:59.680 align:middle line:84%
have been trying
to heal from grief.

00:38:59.680 --> 00:39:02.447 align:middle line:84%
And it is very,
very challenging.

00:39:02.447 --> 00:39:03.280 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yeah, yeah.

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:08.400 align:middle line:84%
The Oracle of the Dead-- one of
the Greek Oracles of the Dead

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:14.150 align:middle line:84%
has been there at
least since 1075 BC.

00:39:14.150 --> 00:39:17.425 align:middle line:90%
So that was 3,000 years ago.

00:39:17.425 --> 00:39:20.760 align:middle line:84%
And so this was
probably-- it's really

00:39:20.760 --> 00:39:23.110 align:middle line:84%
not just an ancient
Greece-- Greek thing,

00:39:23.110 --> 00:39:27.610 align:middle line:84%
this was-- Pretty much all over
the world people had discovered

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:31.250 align:middle line:90%
this, even in prehistoric times.

00:39:31.250 --> 00:39:33.210 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: As a psychiatrist,
do you really

00:39:33.210 --> 00:39:38.040 align:middle line:84%
think that there is such a
thing as getting over grief?

00:39:38.040 --> 00:39:40.730 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: No, but even
more so as a human being,

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:42.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't think there's
any such thing.

00:39:42.510 --> 00:39:45.290 align:middle line:90%


00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:48.630 align:middle line:84%
To some degree,
yes, especially when

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:51.140 align:middle line:84%
the passing is in
the proper order.

00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:53.820 align:middle line:90%


00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:56.390 align:middle line:84%
But I think there's
some things that

00:39:56.390 --> 00:39:59.260 align:middle line:90%
do seem to me irreconcilable.

00:39:59.260 --> 00:40:02.590 align:middle line:84%
And that is, for example,
the loss of a child

00:40:02.590 --> 00:40:07.100 align:middle line:84%
is always just very--
it's a very wrenching kind

00:40:07.100 --> 00:40:08.160 align:middle line:90%
of experience.

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:09.337 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Unexplainable.

00:40:09.337 --> 00:40:09.920 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yeah.

00:40:09.920 --> 00:40:12.530 align:middle line:90%


00:40:12.530 --> 00:40:15.280 align:middle line:84%
And yet, you know, I got
to go on and say here

00:40:15.280 --> 00:40:20.190 align:middle line:84%
that the people who come to
me for counseling about grief

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:21.670 align:middle line:84%
are people who are
having trouble.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:29.070 align:middle line:84%
So I couldn't necessarily say
from that that everybody fits

00:40:29.070 --> 00:40:31.730 align:middle line:84%
in that category, but
at least the people

00:40:31.730 --> 00:40:36.230 align:middle line:84%
I deal with, grief
is always-- you

00:40:36.230 --> 00:40:39.410 align:middle line:90%
never quite get over something.

00:40:39.410 --> 00:40:46.950 align:middle line:84%
I lost my first child
in June of 1970.

00:40:46.950 --> 00:40:49.570 align:middle line:90%
He was 36 hours old.

00:40:49.570 --> 00:40:54.600 align:middle line:84%
And in that era, people
didn't talk about such things.

00:40:54.600 --> 00:40:57.550 align:middle line:84%
A kind of wall of
silence came down.

00:40:57.550 --> 00:41:00.900 align:middle line:84%
And it's only
retrospectively that I

00:41:00.900 --> 00:41:05.090 align:middle line:84%
can see it never
really quite gets over.

00:41:05.090 --> 00:41:05.819 align:middle line:90%
No it doesn't.

00:41:05.819 --> 00:41:06.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It doesn't.

00:41:06.610 --> 00:41:10.520 align:middle line:84%
And after all of your
interviews and helping people

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:12.980 align:middle line:84%
through the
experiences with death,

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:16.720 align:middle line:84%
have you been through that
yourself with the psychomanteum

00:41:16.720 --> 00:41:18.570 align:middle line:84%
and the experiences
with the mirror?

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:20.180 align:middle line:90%
Have you done all that yourself?

00:41:20.180 --> 00:41:20.860 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: I did.

00:41:20.860 --> 00:41:21.360 align:middle line:90%
I did.

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:25.070 align:middle line:84%
And I tried to see my
cookie-baking grandma,

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:26.720 align:middle line:90%
as I call her.

00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:27.641 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:41:27.641 --> 00:41:28.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ever your child?

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:30.556 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: --with whom I
had a wonderful-- no, I

00:41:30.556 --> 00:41:33.940 align:middle line:84%
haven't with my child,
which shows, I think,

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:36.200 align:middle line:90%
maybe how tender this is.

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:39.760 align:middle line:84%
But no, I haven't
tried with my child.

00:41:39.760 --> 00:41:42.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I asked you that
just because it really-- I

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:44.040 align:middle line:84%
love how you answered
that question,

00:41:44.040 --> 00:41:46.170 align:middle line:84%
as a psychiatrist
and as a human.

00:41:46.170 --> 00:41:48.510 align:middle line:84%
It is one of the most
challenging things

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:52.474 align:middle line:84%
to overcome that yet you
really don't ever overcome.

00:41:52.474 --> 00:41:54.140 align:middle line:84%
People have been
trying to figure it out

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:56.670 align:middle line:84%
for thousands and
thousands of years.

00:41:56.670 --> 00:41:59.360 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: The way
I look at it is--

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.330 align:middle line:84%
grief is-- if you think
of yourself as this,

00:42:02.330 --> 00:42:05.500 align:middle line:84%
like all your
consciousness is in here,

00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:08.120 align:middle line:84%
then when you have a
loss of that nature

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:12.800 align:middle line:84%
then it fills up your
whole self with this grief.

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:18.390 align:middle line:84%
And I can tell you here
in the 21st century

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:20.000 align:middle line:90%
that I could go right back to--

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:23.010 align:middle line:84%
If you ask me what
that grief is like,

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:27.300 align:middle line:84%
I would say that it's the same,
but that now the difference

00:42:27.300 --> 00:42:28.400 align:middle line:90%
is this is me.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:31.270 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.270 --> 00:42:35.370 align:middle line:84%
Grief, paradoxically
by working with it,

00:42:35.370 --> 00:42:39.410 align:middle line:84%
you can expand yourself
so that it occupies maybe

00:42:39.410 --> 00:42:44.720 align:middle line:84%
a lesser percentage of your
whole total conscious being.

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:46.970 align:middle line:84%
But the grief in
itself, in my opinion,

00:42:46.970 --> 00:42:50.040 align:middle line:90%
just pretty much is the same.

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:53.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, yet you've
created a life pursuit

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:57.470 align:middle line:84%
of helping people get
through it by creating

00:42:57.470 --> 00:43:01.050 align:middle line:84%
this entire experience, which
we're going to take a look at,

00:43:01.050 --> 00:43:02.890 align:middle line:84%
the psychomanteum
and what that looks

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:05.590 align:middle line:90%
like in a clip in just a minute.

00:43:05.590 --> 00:43:09.530 align:middle line:84%
But your whole mission,
purpose, passion

00:43:09.530 --> 00:43:12.920 align:middle line:84%
is to enable people
to connect with what

00:43:12.920 --> 00:43:15.650 align:middle line:90%
the afterlife could possibly be.

00:43:15.650 --> 00:43:18.510 align:middle line:84%
And does this indeed
ease people who

00:43:18.510 --> 00:43:20.760 align:middle line:84%
have lost loved ones,
in your experience?

00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:22.395 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: No question about it.

00:43:22.395 --> 00:43:23.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It does.

00:43:23.180 --> 00:43:25.030 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: I think it's
been demonstrated

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:29.200 align:middle line:84%
in numerous studies
actually, as I understand,

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:33.900 align:middle line:84%
that just reading about
near-death experiences

00:43:33.900 --> 00:43:36.580 align:middle line:84%
or hearing someone
talk about them

00:43:36.580 --> 00:43:40.050 align:middle line:84%
brings comfort to
people who are grieving.

00:43:40.050 --> 00:43:45.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, I have heard of
studies of that nature,

00:43:45.200 --> 00:43:49.010 align:middle line:84%
but I'm saying that from
my own personal experience

00:43:49.010 --> 00:43:52.360 align:middle line:84%
because I just hear from
people all the time,

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:56.820 align:middle line:84%
from the very beginning I began
to lecture on this in 1969

00:43:56.820 --> 00:44:00.110 align:middle line:84%
and 1970, that I
heard people say

00:44:00.110 --> 00:44:03.520 align:middle line:84%
that just hearing
about these experiences

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:07.859 align:middle line:84%
gives them some sort of comfort
in dealing with their losses.

00:44:07.859 --> 00:44:08.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:44:08.650 --> 00:44:09.150 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:44:09.150 --> 00:44:11.310 align:middle line:84%
When we come back, we're
going to take a look

00:44:11.310 --> 00:44:14.170 align:middle line:84%
at what these experiences are
where Dr. Moody takes people

00:44:14.170 --> 00:44:15.900 align:middle line:90%
into the chamber and the mirror.

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:18.730 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
psychomanteum experience.

00:44:18.730 --> 00:44:21.650 align:middle line:84%
And we'll take a look at
that when we come back.

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:22.460 align:middle line:90%
This is Lisa Garr.

00:44:22.460 --> 00:44:24.130 align:middle line:90%
We'll be right back.

00:44:24.130 --> 00:44:24.910 align:middle line:90%
Welcome back.

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:27.460 align:middle line:84%
My guest is Dr. Raymond
Moody, and we're

00:44:27.460 --> 00:44:32.300 align:middle line:84%
talking about, God, so many
great things-- life after life.

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:34.300 align:middle line:84%
What we were talking about
before the break were

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:37.270 align:middle line:84%
these controlled experiences,
these controlled circumstances,

00:44:37.270 --> 00:44:40.080 align:middle line:84%
that you take people through
called a psychomanteum.

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:41.660 align:middle line:90%
What does that word mean?

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:43.350 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, it
basically means

00:44:43.350 --> 00:44:47.247 align:middle line:84%
a place where you go to
converse with the deceased.

00:44:47.247 --> 00:44:48.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Of course it does.

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:51.560 align:middle line:90%


00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:54.610 align:middle line:84%
This isn't normal breakfast
table conversation.

00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:57.740 align:middle line:84%
So a place that you go to
converse with the deceased.

00:44:57.740 --> 00:45:01.360 align:middle line:84%
And you created this
out of a need for people

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:04.010 align:middle line:90%
to heal from grief, yes?

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:06.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Oh, Lisa, that is
a wonderful thing to say.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:08.460 align:middle line:84%
That makes me seem
like a nice guy,

00:45:08.460 --> 00:45:10.650 align:middle line:84%
but I'll just be
completely honest.

00:45:10.650 --> 00:45:11.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: The reason I
was interested in this

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:17.670 align:middle line:84%
initially was that
this was really

00:45:17.670 --> 00:45:21.940 align:middle line:84%
a very important
institution in the creation

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:24.910 align:middle line:84%
of the entire Western
way of thinking.

00:45:24.910 --> 00:45:26.890 align:middle line:84%
And see, I was a
professor of logic.

00:45:26.890 --> 00:45:27.730 align:middle line:90%
I love logic.

00:45:27.730 --> 00:45:29.550 align:middle line:90%
And wild as it may seem--

00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:30.594 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:45:30.594 --> 00:45:32.760 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: I'm not going to
talk about this in detail,

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:37.170 align:middle line:84%
but the Western logic came
from these Oracles of the Dead.

00:45:37.170 --> 00:45:39.232 align:middle line:84%
It's a long story, but
that's how it got started.

00:45:39.232 --> 00:45:40.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: An interesting
one, though.

00:45:40.690 --> 00:45:42.010 align:middle line:90%
Give me the two minute on that.

00:45:42.010 --> 00:45:45.530 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, basically
the philosopher Parmenides,

00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:47.110 align:middle line:90%
who was the person who--

00:45:47.110 --> 00:45:49.640 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: I remember studying
this in your course.

00:45:49.640 --> 00:45:52.760 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: In 500 BC,
Parmenides, who's

00:45:52.760 --> 00:45:57.270 align:middle line:84%
regarded as the father
of deductive logic, first

00:45:57.270 --> 00:45:59.950 align:middle line:84%
was able to articulate
the notion of truth.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:03.170 align:middle line:84%
That is, that some things
are the case independently

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:05.210 align:middle line:90%
of what anybody thinks about it.

00:46:05.210 --> 00:46:09.430 align:middle line:84%
And that was too abstract
an idea for people

00:46:09.430 --> 00:46:12.360 align:middle line:84%
in a preliterate culture
to grasp for reasons

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:13.470 align:middle line:90%
I won't go into.

00:46:13.470 --> 00:46:15.730 align:middle line:84%
But they were trying
to solve the problem,

00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:17.560 align:middle line:84%
and it was Parmenides
who did it.

00:46:17.560 --> 00:46:21.310 align:middle line:84%
And Parmenides in his
day job, as it were,

00:46:21.310 --> 00:46:24.030 align:middle line:84%
was a worker at one of
these Oracles of the Dead.

00:46:24.030 --> 00:46:27.190 align:middle line:84%
And he would get
in a cave, and he

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:31.630 align:middle line:84%
was known as an
iatromantis-- or prophet

00:46:31.630 --> 00:46:34.630 align:middle line:84%
doctor is more or
less the translation.

00:46:34.630 --> 00:46:40.380 align:middle line:84%
But he would go through--
he would lie in the cave,

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:43.300 align:middle line:84%
presumably lie
stock still, and he

00:46:43.300 --> 00:46:47.370 align:middle line:84%
would have these visionary
voyages into the other world.

00:46:47.370 --> 00:46:49.620 align:middle line:84%
And on one of his
trips over there,

00:46:49.620 --> 00:46:54.440 align:middle line:84%
he met this goddess who divulged
the first written-out logical

00:46:54.440 --> 00:46:57.110 align:middle line:90%
deduction in the form of a song.

00:46:57.110 --> 00:47:00.650 align:middle line:84%
And this was-- in
effect, you could

00:47:00.650 --> 00:47:05.390 align:middle line:84%
say histories of Western
thought make a dividing line

00:47:05.390 --> 00:47:08.570 align:middle line:84%
at Parmenides, because
things after Parmenides-- it

00:47:08.570 --> 00:47:12.790 align:middle line:84%
was a totally different world
after he discovered this.

00:47:12.790 --> 00:47:17.250 align:middle line:84%
And he, from his
point of view anyway,

00:47:17.250 --> 00:47:19.280 align:middle line:84%
brought this
information that was

00:47:19.280 --> 00:47:24.400 align:middle line:84%
the foundation of Western
logic back from the other side.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:26.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's how I got
interested in it.

00:47:26.590 --> 00:47:29.300 align:middle line:84%
And then when I
started doing it,

00:47:29.300 --> 00:47:33.150 align:middle line:84%
I realized that the people
that I was taking through it

00:47:33.150 --> 00:47:40.030 align:middle line:84%
were-- felt like they had
benefited in their grief

00:47:40.030 --> 00:47:43.250 align:middle line:84%
or moved on in their grief,
and it helped them and so on.

00:47:43.250 --> 00:47:45.690 align:middle line:84%
So that was a great-- that
was a great side effect.

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:49.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you got into it
from a place of curiosity

00:47:49.440 --> 00:47:52.511 align:middle line:84%
about logic, and then you wound
up effectively helping people.

00:47:52.511 --> 00:47:54.260 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yeah, and
then I realized-- well,

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:56.400 align:middle line:84%
I really didn't
anticipate it, but I

00:47:56.400 --> 00:47:58.250 align:middle line:84%
saw that people who
went through this

00:47:58.250 --> 00:48:01.411 align:middle line:84%
actually did gain
relief from their grief.

00:48:01.411 --> 00:48:02.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We have a
clip of this, so I

00:48:02.910 --> 00:48:05.100 align:middle line:84%
want people to have the
experience of taking

00:48:05.100 --> 00:48:07.445 align:middle line:84%
a look at what
we're talking about.

00:48:07.445 --> 00:48:08.720 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:48:08.720 --> 00:48:11.400 align:middle line:84%
>>The success of the
modern psychomanteum,

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:14.470 align:middle line:84%
both at his own
facility and elsewhere,

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:17.380 align:middle line:84%
has led Raymond Moody to
direct his lifelong research

00:48:17.380 --> 00:48:22.080 align:middle line:84%
into the nature of death
yet one step further.

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:24.380 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: It's well
known that people

00:48:24.380 --> 00:48:29.360 align:middle line:84%
on their deathbeds, dying people
who do go on to die, very often

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:33.360 align:middle line:84%
just prior to their death will
say something like, oh, why,

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:36.805 align:middle line:84%
there's mother, or there's
grandpa, or whatever.

00:48:36.805 --> 00:48:40.090 align:middle line:84%
In other words, it seems
that at the moment of death

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:43.960 align:middle line:84%
they see apparitions of
departed relatives and friends

00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:47.440 align:middle line:84%
who seem to be there,
as it were, to meet them

00:48:47.440 --> 00:48:50.700 align:middle line:84%
or to help them through
this transition.

00:48:50.700 --> 00:48:55.180 align:middle line:84%
From time to time, physicians,
nurses, other people

00:48:55.180 --> 00:48:58.050 align:middle line:84%
at the bedside of
dying patients will

00:48:58.050 --> 00:49:01.340 align:middle line:84%
say that they have an
experience in which they

00:49:01.340 --> 00:49:06.350 align:middle line:84%
seem to see the person leave
the body at the moment of death.

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:11.130 align:middle line:84%
Also, I've talk with a number
of physicians and nurses

00:49:11.130 --> 00:49:15.560 align:middle line:84%
and also friends of
people who have died,

00:49:15.560 --> 00:49:18.590 align:middle line:84%
relatives of people
who've died, who tell me

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:20.770 align:middle line:84%
that they have undergone
what I can only

00:49:20.770 --> 00:49:23.660 align:middle line:84%
call empathetic
near-death experiences.

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:26.270 align:middle line:84%
These are experiences in which,
for instance, the physician

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:30.050 align:middle line:84%
who's resuscitating someone
who's very close to them

00:49:30.050 --> 00:49:32.710 align:middle line:84%
will say that, as this
person dies and begins

00:49:32.710 --> 00:49:35.510 align:middle line:84%
to slip into this experience
of seeing the tunnel

00:49:35.510 --> 00:49:38.190 align:middle line:84%
and going out of
the body and so on,

00:49:38.190 --> 00:49:41.160 align:middle line:84%
that the physician himself
or herself will begin

00:49:41.160 --> 00:49:43.920 align:middle line:84%
to experience
this, will actually

00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:47.520 align:middle line:84%
enter into the near-death
experience of the dying person.

00:49:47.520 --> 00:49:48.820 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:50.990 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you feel
that those people that

00:49:50.990 --> 00:49:52.740 align:middle line:84%
had the experiences,
the shared death

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:55.400 align:middle line:84%
experiences, that they
have to-- that they're

00:49:55.400 --> 00:49:57.330 align:middle line:84%
related to that
person in some way,

00:49:57.330 --> 00:50:01.060 align:middle line:84%
that they're within
their realm of relations?

00:50:01.060 --> 00:50:02.520 align:middle line:90%
Do you know what I mean by that?

00:50:02.520 --> 00:50:05.900 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Oh, well,
actually, Lisa, no.

00:50:05.900 --> 00:50:10.170 align:middle line:84%
It's very interesting,
because I hear the same thing

00:50:10.170 --> 00:50:15.600 align:middle line:84%
from doctors who were just
called in to see a patient.

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:21.360 align:middle line:84%
They didn't know who it was, and
they were on call or whatever.

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:23.660 align:middle line:84%
And they had to
resuscitate a stranger,

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:25.760 align:middle line:84%
and maybe the
person died during.

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:29.720 align:middle line:84%
But they say that they see this
light leave the body and so on.

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:33.520 align:middle line:84%
So apparently, in
the general case,

00:50:33.520 --> 00:50:37.210 align:middle line:84%
yes, usually it's the
people at the bedside

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:39.630 align:middle line:84%
or loved ones and
friends and so on,

00:50:39.630 --> 00:50:42.700 align:middle line:84%
but I've had plenty of cases,
too, of physicians who just

00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:45.490 align:middle line:84%
called in to see a
perfect stranger who

00:50:45.490 --> 00:50:48.660 align:middle line:84%
was in the process of
dying and saw this light

00:50:48.660 --> 00:50:52.520 align:middle line:84%
or saw the person leave
their bodies and so on.

00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:54.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This just
begs the question,

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:56.820 align:middle line:84%
and you're the perfect
person to ask about this.

00:50:56.820 --> 00:50:59.760 align:middle line:84%
I need to ask you about
parallel universes,

00:50:59.760 --> 00:51:03.770 align:middle line:84%
and multidimensional realities,
and different dimensions.

00:51:03.770 --> 00:51:07.880 align:middle line:84%
This really begs the question
of, do those dimensions exist?

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:11.170 align:middle line:84%
Do you have any evidence of
those dimensions existing

00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:14.850 align:middle line:90%
in your experience?

00:51:14.850 --> 00:51:18.680 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Quite a number,
in absolute terms

00:51:18.680 --> 00:51:22.070 align:middle line:84%
but not in percentage terms,
of the people with a near-death

00:51:22.070 --> 00:51:26.470 align:middle line:84%
experience-- a small
percentage of them,

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:28.170 align:middle line:84%
and variably these
are people who

00:51:28.170 --> 00:51:30.980 align:middle line:84%
had extremely lengthy
cardiac arrests that

00:51:30.980 --> 00:51:35.050 align:middle line:84%
went far beyond that-- we all
hear the five-minute rule,

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:37.590 align:middle line:84%
that beyond five minutes
you can't resuscitate

00:51:37.590 --> 00:51:39.610 align:middle line:90%
because the brain is damaged.

00:51:39.610 --> 00:51:42.360 align:middle line:84%
And as a rule of
thumb, that's terrific,

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:45.820 align:middle line:84%
but in many cases also there's
just-- it doesn't work out.

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:48.630 align:middle line:84%
And we have cases
of people who had

00:51:48.630 --> 00:51:51.450 align:middle line:84%
extremely lengthy
cardiac arrests and yet

00:51:51.450 --> 00:51:55.280 align:middle line:90%
who've recovered and were fine.

00:51:55.280 --> 00:51:57.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And they say
that's less than 1%,

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:00.450 align:middle line:90%
but I've spoken to several.

00:52:00.450 --> 00:52:05.000 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: And so these people
with the extremely lengthy

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:08.260 align:middle line:84%
cardiac arrests will
say, yes, that they

00:52:08.260 --> 00:52:12.890 align:middle line:84%
see that there are different
levels or dimensions.

00:52:12.890 --> 00:52:15.490 align:middle line:84%
And I've heard people
say, for example,

00:52:15.490 --> 00:52:19.580 align:middle line:84%
that they see into one
dimension that is entirely,

00:52:19.580 --> 00:52:23.290 align:middle line:84%
in effect, an institution of
higher learning, that people

00:52:23.290 --> 00:52:25.920 align:middle line:84%
are there pursuing
knowledge and truth.

00:52:25.920 --> 00:52:28.840 align:middle line:84%
And that other people--
these people say also

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:33.140 align:middle line:84%
they see another dimension of
reality, which is described,

00:52:33.140 --> 00:52:35.200 align:middle line:84%
or people try to
put it into words

00:52:35.200 --> 00:52:37.680 align:middle line:90%
by saying, cities of light.

00:52:37.680 --> 00:52:39.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's always
about the light.

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:39.900 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yeah.

00:52:39.900 --> 00:52:42.540 align:middle line:84%
And they say that's it's
like a civilization,

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:47.239 align:middle line:84%
but it's not constructed
of matter but of light.

00:52:47.239 --> 00:52:48.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That makes sense.

00:52:48.280 --> 00:52:50.990 align:middle line:84%
So as we speak right
here, right now,

00:52:50.990 --> 00:52:55.610 align:middle line:84%
there very well could be
parallel or multiple dimensions

00:52:55.610 --> 00:53:00.590 align:middle line:84%
happening at this very
time, non locally.

00:53:00.590 --> 00:53:04.710 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, you know, that's
what even physicists tell us.

00:53:04.710 --> 00:53:06.790 align:middle line:84%
Not all physicists,
but some physicists

00:53:06.790 --> 00:53:12.340 align:middle line:84%
are into this kind of view
that all of the possibilities

00:53:12.340 --> 00:53:13.560 align:middle line:90%
are realized.

00:53:13.560 --> 00:53:14.609 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:53:14.609 --> 00:53:15.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Thank

00:53:15.150 --> 00:53:16.100 align:middle line:90%
you for--

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:19.230 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: On one interpretation
of quantum mechanics,

00:53:19.230 --> 00:53:23.530 align:middle line:84%
for example, all of the
choices, all of the bifurcation

00:53:23.530 --> 00:53:26.770 align:middle line:84%
or dividing points,
that there's some sense

00:53:26.770 --> 00:53:30.791 align:middle line:84%
in which all the different
possibilities are realized.

00:53:30.791 --> 00:53:32.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, from
your perspective,

00:53:32.290 --> 00:53:34.250 align:middle line:84%
where you bring people
into the psychomanteum

00:53:34.250 --> 00:53:37.040 align:middle line:84%
in this controlled circumstance
where they can actually

00:53:37.040 --> 00:53:39.790 align:middle line:84%
access the apparitions
of other people,

00:53:39.790 --> 00:53:41.910 align:middle line:84%
or if you speak
to people who have

00:53:41.910 --> 00:53:45.900 align:middle line:84%
had these multiple-dimensional
near-death experiences--

00:53:45.900 --> 00:53:48.874 align:middle line:90%
I myself have been through that.

00:53:48.874 --> 00:53:50.290 align:middle line:84%
So I just had to
ask the question.

00:53:50.290 --> 00:53:52.690 align:middle line:84%
So I want to get back into
the near-death experience

00:53:52.690 --> 00:53:54.540 align:middle line:84%
and where people
go to the light.

00:53:54.540 --> 00:53:57.890 align:middle line:84%
We hear-- You've spoken so much
about this, about the light,

00:53:57.890 --> 00:54:00.980 align:middle line:84%
and over and over you
hear people speaking

00:54:00.980 --> 00:54:03.970 align:middle line:84%
about this idea of
going to the light.

00:54:03.970 --> 00:54:05.760 align:middle line:84%
And we have a clip
of this, so I want

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:08.140 align:middle line:84%
to show people what this
is and a little bit more

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:09.520 align:middle line:90%
about what that experience is.

00:54:09.520 --> 00:54:12.309 align:middle line:90%
Multiple people talking about.

00:54:12.309 --> 00:54:16.660 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:54:16.660 --> 00:54:20.520 align:middle line:84%
>>This is the most
wonderful part of it.

00:54:20.520 --> 00:54:23.250 align:middle line:90%
This is a warm, loving light.

00:54:23.250 --> 00:54:27.140 align:middle line:84%
It's the most
masculine, but it also

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:32.350 align:middle line:84%
has overtones of mother
love, sisterly love.

00:54:32.350 --> 00:54:34.510 align:middle line:90%
This just pulsates around.

00:54:34.510 --> 00:54:38.240 align:middle line:84%
He has totally accepted
me and forgiven me

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:41.550 align:middle line:84%
for everything I've ever
done, but can I forgive myself

00:54:41.550 --> 00:54:44.300 align:middle line:84%
for some of these selfish
things I have done?

00:54:44.300 --> 00:54:47.710 align:middle line:84%
>>And there was this
unconditional love

00:54:47.710 --> 00:54:53.590 align:middle line:84%
like most parents have
for their children,

00:54:53.590 --> 00:54:58.050 align:middle line:84%
that no matter how
bad I might have been

00:54:58.050 --> 00:55:03.690 align:middle line:84%
or-- that I was totally
loved and totally understood,

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:08.502 align:middle line:90%
and-- just wonderful love.

00:55:08.502 --> 00:55:09.960 align:middle line:84%
>>And sitting there,
wondering what

00:55:09.960 --> 00:55:13.750 align:middle line:84%
to do next, when suddenly that
room became flooded with light.

00:55:13.750 --> 00:55:17.990 align:middle line:84%
And then three things happened
simultaneously just like that.

00:55:17.990 --> 00:55:20.259 align:middle line:84%
Something deep inside of
the spiritual being sitting

00:55:20.259 --> 00:55:22.800 align:middle line:84%
on the side of the bed looking
at the corpse lying in the bed

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:27.870 align:middle line:84%
was told to stand up, you're in
the presence of the son of God.

00:55:27.870 --> 00:55:30.690 align:middle line:84%
Out of that light stepped the
most amazing being I have ever

00:55:30.690 --> 00:55:33.360 align:middle line:84%
been in the presence of, the
most powerfully built male

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:35.220 align:middle line:90%
I have ever seen.

00:55:35.220 --> 00:55:37.580 align:middle line:84%
And now, once being in the
presence of the being who

00:55:37.580 --> 00:55:40.954 align:middle line:84%
knows everything about you, to
know that he totally accepts

00:55:40.954 --> 00:55:42.370 align:middle line:84%
you and totally
loves you, I never

00:55:42.370 --> 00:55:45.100 align:middle line:84%
wanted to leave this being
again under any circumstance.

00:55:45.100 --> 00:55:46.570 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:55:46.570 --> 00:55:48.120 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You said
that he was really

00:55:48.120 --> 00:55:50.100 align:middle line:84%
one of the most impactful
people in your life.

00:55:50.100 --> 00:55:52.910 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Oh yeah, George Ritchie
was the finest human being

00:55:52.910 --> 00:55:54.552 align:middle line:84%
I ever knew in my
life, no question.

00:55:54.552 --> 00:55:56.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: He seems like he
was an amazing person.

00:55:56.510 --> 00:55:57.310 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, he was.

00:55:57.310 --> 00:55:57.890 align:middle line:90%
He was just incredible.

00:55:57.890 --> 00:55:59.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Why did he
impact you so much?

00:55:59.500 --> 00:56:02.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well-- Well,
you know, George-- I

00:56:02.390 --> 00:56:04.770 align:middle line:84%
lived in the same community
George Ritchie did

00:56:04.770 --> 00:56:06.950 align:middle line:84%
for some time, and
you get to know people

00:56:06.950 --> 00:56:09.140 align:middle line:84%
like that because of
the things that you

00:56:09.140 --> 00:56:12.110 align:middle line:84%
hear about other people
telling you about.

00:56:12.110 --> 00:56:18.000 align:middle line:84%
And he was just so completely
kind and loving and yet

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:19.990 align:middle line:90%
just totally human, too.

00:56:19.990 --> 00:56:25.130 align:middle line:84%
And when I heard his
experience in 1965,

00:56:25.130 --> 00:56:28.030 align:middle line:84%
I was an undergraduate
at UVA, and I

00:56:28.030 --> 00:56:30.680 align:middle line:84%
knew that something
had happened to me when

00:56:30.680 --> 00:56:33.190 align:middle line:84%
I heard that experience,
which has played out

00:56:33.190 --> 00:56:34.890 align:middle line:90%
in the rest of my life.

00:56:34.890 --> 00:56:39.510 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out,
actually-- this

00:56:39.510 --> 00:56:44.780 align:middle line:84%
isn't-- my-- George's experience
took place at Camp Barkeley,

00:56:44.780 --> 00:56:52.420 align:middle line:84%
Texas in December 1943 when he
was a recruit into the Army.

00:56:52.420 --> 00:56:59.770 align:middle line:84%
And hearing the story in 1965
so profoundly influenced me.

00:56:59.770 --> 00:57:01.640 align:middle line:84%
Then I went on this
quest of interviewing

00:57:01.640 --> 00:57:03.430 align:middle line:90%
all these other people.

00:57:03.430 --> 00:57:07.240 align:middle line:84%
And the book was published
in November of '75.

00:57:07.240 --> 00:57:11.450 align:middle line:84%
And just before I published
it, I called Dr. Ritchie

00:57:11.450 --> 00:57:14.650 align:middle line:84%
and asked if I could
dedicate the book to him.

00:57:14.650 --> 00:57:18.750 align:middle line:84%
So that was the only contact
in those intervening 10 years.

00:57:18.750 --> 00:57:22.820 align:middle line:84%
Now, flash forward
to March of '76.

00:57:22.820 --> 00:57:27.320 align:middle line:84%
I was talking about this with
my father, who by then had heard

00:57:27.320 --> 00:57:30.900 align:middle line:84%
a tape of Dr.
Ritchie's experience.

00:57:30.900 --> 00:57:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And I can tell you exactly
what Dr.-- my father said.

00:57:35.210 --> 00:57:38.560 align:middle line:84%
He said, huh, that's
really interesting.

00:57:38.560 --> 00:57:44.770 align:middle line:84%
George Ritchie, Camp Barkeley,
Texas, December 1943.

00:57:44.770 --> 00:57:49.500 align:middle line:84%
He said, you know, I was
there and so were you.

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:51.960 align:middle line:84%
My mom and dad are from
Porterdale, Georgia.

00:57:51.960 --> 00:57:54.860 align:middle line:84%
George is from
Richmond, Virginia.

00:57:54.860 --> 00:57:58.840 align:middle line:84%
But my dad went
to Camp Barkeley,

00:57:58.840 --> 00:58:03.340 align:middle line:84%
Texas in early
September 1943 so he

00:58:03.340 --> 00:58:05.920 align:middle line:84%
could go to officers
candidate school.

00:58:05.920 --> 00:58:09.150 align:middle line:84%
I was conceived in
late September 1943.

00:58:09.150 --> 00:58:12.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness, wow.

00:58:12.200 --> 00:58:16.290 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: George's experience
was December 24, 1943.

00:58:16.290 --> 00:58:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And Mom and Dad moved away from
Camp Barkeley in December 29,

00:58:21.920 --> 00:58:22.680 align:middle line:90%
1943.

00:58:22.680 --> 00:58:24.760 align:middle line:90%
So I was there in utero--

00:58:24.760 --> 00:58:25.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: In spirit.

00:58:25.850 --> 00:58:27.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: --when
this experience took

00:58:27.390 --> 00:58:28.940 align:middle line:90%
place that changed my life.

00:58:28.940 --> 00:58:32.306 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't know about
it until "Life After Life"

00:58:32.306 --> 00:58:33.430 align:middle line:90%
had already been published.

00:58:33.430 --> 00:58:37.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How many times
do you see people

00:58:37.290 --> 00:58:42.935 align:middle line:84%
in groups communicating with
each other in the afterlife?

00:58:42.935 --> 00:58:44.560 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Now, that's
interesting, Lisa.

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:48.990 align:middle line:90%


00:58:48.990 --> 00:58:52.470 align:middle line:84%
Nothing really comes to mind,
except occasionally I've

00:58:52.470 --> 00:58:56.790 align:middle line:84%
had cases of
near-death experiences

00:58:56.790 --> 00:58:59.540 align:middle line:84%
where two people
at once came close

00:58:59.540 --> 00:59:02.300 align:middle line:84%
to death in the course
of an accident and so on.

00:59:02.300 --> 00:59:06.490 align:middle line:84%
And then, subsequently, even
when they were still separated,

00:59:06.490 --> 00:59:10.860 align:middle line:84%
talked about, yeah, I saw--
and they had this communication

00:59:10.860 --> 00:59:13.030 align:middle line:84%
even when they were
out of their bodies.

00:59:13.030 --> 00:59:13.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:59:13.960 --> 00:59:15.580 align:middle line:84%
What's the difference
between life

00:59:15.580 --> 00:59:18.330 align:middle line:90%
after life and reincarnation?

00:59:18.330 --> 00:59:22.370 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, you know, out
of the thousands of people

00:59:22.370 --> 00:59:25.310 align:middle line:84%
that I've talked with who
had near-death experiences,

00:59:25.310 --> 00:59:27.030 align:middle line:84%
there were only
three of them that

00:59:27.030 --> 00:59:30.950 align:middle line:84%
had some experience within
the near-death experience that

00:59:30.950 --> 00:59:34.430 align:middle line:84%
led them to think that
there's a reincarnation.

00:59:34.430 --> 00:59:39.420 align:middle line:84%
But the great majority of the
others who didn't see anything

00:59:39.420 --> 00:59:42.040 align:middle line:84%
related to reincarnation,
nonetheless

00:59:42.040 --> 00:59:45.350 align:middle line:84%
it seems to wake them up at
least to the possibility.

00:59:45.350 --> 00:59:48.350 align:middle line:84%
People will say things like,
I didn't really say anything

00:59:48.350 --> 00:59:51.120 align:middle line:84%
over there than indicated to
me that there's reincarnation,

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:54.380 align:middle line:84%
because I only went to a
certain point and came back,

00:59:54.380 --> 00:59:58.100 align:middle line:84%
but they seem to
be emotionally more

00:59:58.100 --> 01:00:02.047 align:middle line:84%
accepting of that possibility
after a near-death experience.

01:00:02.047 --> 01:00:03.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is there a
theme in the people

01:00:03.630 --> 01:00:06.170 align:middle line:84%
that you've interviewed
as to why they come back?

01:00:06.170 --> 01:00:09.640 align:middle line:84%
Do they come back to a-- because
of a calling of a loved one

01:00:09.640 --> 01:00:12.060 align:middle line:84%
that's calling them
back or a mission?

01:00:12.060 --> 01:00:15.930 align:middle line:84%
Or have you noticed a through
line with these people?

01:00:15.930 --> 01:00:18.710 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Sometimes people, when
they're over there, are told,

01:00:18.710 --> 01:00:21.080 align:middle line:84%
you've got to go back,
you've got things left to do.

01:00:21.080 --> 01:00:24.610 align:middle line:84%
But they're not told what that
is that they're supposed to do,

01:00:24.610 --> 01:00:26.950 align:middle line:84%
which can be very
frustrating for them.

01:00:26.950 --> 01:00:29.870 align:middle line:90%


01:00:29.870 --> 01:00:32.950 align:middle line:84%
And yet, having known some
of these people for decades,

01:00:32.950 --> 01:00:36.530 align:middle line:84%
I see that in the passage of
time, they sort of wake up

01:00:36.530 --> 01:00:40.390 align:middle line:84%
and they say, oh, that's
why I had to come back.

01:00:40.390 --> 01:00:44.000 align:middle line:84%
Then other people just don't
know why they were sent back.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:47.320 align:middle line:84%
And some people
are given a choice.

01:00:47.320 --> 01:00:49.090 align:middle line:84%
They're told that
they can either

01:00:49.090 --> 01:00:52.200 align:middle line:84%
go on with the experience
they're having or go back

01:00:52.200 --> 01:00:53.820 align:middle line:90%
to the life they were leading.

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:56.210 align:middle line:84%
And not too surprisingly,
all of those

01:00:56.210 --> 01:00:59.170 align:middle line:84%
that were given that
choice that I interviewed

01:00:59.170 --> 01:01:00.160 align:middle line:90%
chose to come back.

01:01:00.160 --> 01:01:03.380 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting in
this, they almost always

01:01:03.380 --> 01:01:04.960 align:middle line:90%
give the same reason.

01:01:04.960 --> 01:01:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And that is that, for
themselves, they would rather

01:01:08.100 --> 01:01:09.720 align:middle line:84%
have stayed in that
light, but they

01:01:09.720 --> 01:01:11.960 align:middle line:84%
chose to come back
because they had

01:01:11.960 --> 01:01:13.730 align:middle line:90%
young children left to raise.

01:01:13.730 --> 01:01:16.110 align:middle line:84%
That's the most common
thing people say.

01:01:16.110 --> 01:01:20.450 align:middle line:84%
Or they say that, I spent my
life preparing for a helping

01:01:20.450 --> 01:01:24.776 align:middle line:84%
profession and I chose to
come back to complete that.

01:01:24.776 --> 01:01:26.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I imagine
that this could

01:01:26.150 --> 01:01:29.490 align:middle line:84%
be very healing for
children who are now

01:01:29.490 --> 01:01:31.380 align:middle line:84%
adults who have lost
parents when they

01:01:31.380 --> 01:01:34.850 align:middle line:84%
were young, or at
any age really,

01:01:34.850 --> 01:01:40.290 align:middle line:84%
to be able to know that
that parent went to a place,

01:01:40.290 --> 01:01:43.625 align:middle line:84%
that the transition
was a good place.

01:01:43.625 --> 01:01:44.900 align:middle line:90%
At least this could be--

01:01:44.900 --> 01:01:46.250 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Yes.

01:01:46.250 --> 01:01:49.670 align:middle line:84%
And then we always got
to think that-- even

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:53.830 align:middle line:84%
people with near-death
experiences tell me that when--

01:01:53.830 --> 01:01:56.860 align:middle line:84%
after they come back from
this and they lose a loved

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:58.165 align:middle line:90%
one, that they still grieve.

01:01:58.165 --> 01:01:59.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, of course.

01:01:59.110 --> 01:02:01.770 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Because-- and what
it really does, I think,

01:02:01.770 --> 01:02:05.130 align:middle line:84%
is to put the locus
of the grieving more--

01:02:05.130 --> 01:02:06.800 align:middle line:90%
it makes it more obvious.

01:02:06.800 --> 01:02:09.730 align:middle line:84%
Because people with
near-death experiences

01:02:09.730 --> 01:02:13.490 align:middle line:84%
say that when they lose a
loved one that they realize,

01:02:13.490 --> 01:02:17.840 align:middle line:84%
of course, my loved one
is OK, but I miss them,

01:02:17.840 --> 01:02:20.430 align:middle line:90%
is the thing that they get.

01:02:20.430 --> 01:02:24.380 align:middle line:84%
Losing a parent is a very
difficult thing for a child.

01:02:24.380 --> 01:02:28.620 align:middle line:84%
And recent studies
indicate that 20

01:02:28.620 --> 01:02:32.420 align:middle line:84%
seems to be the line
there that, if you lose

01:02:32.420 --> 01:02:35.740 align:middle line:84%
a parent before you're
age 20, that it's

01:02:35.740 --> 01:02:38.810 align:middle line:84%
very difficult for
people to reconcile.

01:02:38.810 --> 01:02:42.690 align:middle line:84%
So I'm trying to stay around
for another nine years.

01:02:42.690 --> 01:02:44.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Why nine years?

01:02:44.130 --> 01:02:46.470 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, because I've
got an 11-year-old daughter,

01:02:46.470 --> 01:02:47.386 align:middle line:90%
and she's my youngest.

01:02:47.386 --> 01:02:48.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

01:02:48.390 --> 01:02:52.180 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: So I figure that gives
good reason to try to stay.

01:02:52.180 --> 01:02:54.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Would you stick around
a little longer for us, please?

01:02:54.850 --> 01:02:56.820 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Insofar
as it's possible.

01:02:56.820 --> 01:03:00.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You told me a story
about someone who you knew who

01:03:00.560 --> 01:03:04.252 align:middle line:84%
was adopted and went
back to discover--

01:03:04.252 --> 01:03:04.960 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes.

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:08.620 align:middle line:84%
In recent months, I've come
across the most amazing

01:03:08.620 --> 01:03:11.950 align:middle line:84%
near-death experience
I've ever heard.

01:03:11.950 --> 01:03:16.460 align:middle line:84%
And this is by an
absolutely wonderful man

01:03:16.460 --> 01:03:19.620 align:middle line:90%
named Eben Alexander III.

01:03:19.620 --> 01:03:22.880 align:middle line:90%
E-B-E-N Alexander III.

01:03:22.880 --> 01:03:28.740 align:middle line:84%
And Eben, to sketch out
his qualifications for you,

01:03:28.740 --> 01:03:31.600 align:middle line:84%
Eben was professor
of neurosurgery

01:03:31.600 --> 01:03:35.280 align:middle line:90%
at Harvard for 15 years.

01:03:35.280 --> 01:03:38.730 align:middle line:84%
And his list of
scientific publications

01:03:38.730 --> 01:03:42.620 align:middle line:84%
is like this, including
some amazing discoveries

01:03:42.620 --> 01:03:45.270 align:middle line:90%
in neurosciences and so on.

01:03:45.270 --> 01:03:48.550 align:middle line:84%
Well, Eben, like many other
people in his profession,

01:03:48.550 --> 01:03:51.150 align:middle line:84%
had been sort of taken
up in this doctrine

01:03:51.150 --> 01:03:55.010 align:middle line:84%
that consciousness is a
secondary byproduct of brain

01:03:55.010 --> 01:03:58.010 align:middle line:84%
process and has no
independent reality.

01:03:58.010 --> 01:04:02.940 align:middle line:84%
That's just what he had always
assumed from his profession.

01:04:02.940 --> 01:04:10.860 align:middle line:84%
And in November of 2008, Eben
developed a horrific condition

01:04:10.860 --> 01:04:16.080 align:middle line:84%
called E. coli meningitis, which
is unheard of among adults.

01:04:16.080 --> 01:04:18.750 align:middle line:84%
It's occasionally with
infants, but almost

01:04:18.750 --> 01:04:20.210 align:middle line:90%
unheard of of adults.

01:04:20.210 --> 01:04:24.080 align:middle line:84%
And in those few cases where
it happens with adults,

01:04:24.080 --> 01:04:27.510 align:middle line:84%
it's virtually unsurvivable,
and those who do survive

01:04:27.510 --> 01:04:29.310 align:middle line:90%
are impaired.

01:04:29.310 --> 01:04:31.190 align:middle line:90%
So that was the situation.

01:04:31.190 --> 01:04:35.410 align:middle line:84%
So in November of 2008,
he developed this illness.

01:04:35.410 --> 01:04:37.790 align:middle line:84%
His colleagues, no doubt
concerned about him.

01:04:37.790 --> 01:04:40.620 align:middle line:84%
He was carefully monitored
throughout this illness.

01:04:40.620 --> 01:04:43.420 align:middle line:90%
He went into a week-long coma.

01:04:43.420 --> 01:04:47.060 align:middle line:84%
And the distribution
of the lesions

01:04:47.060 --> 01:04:50.590 align:middle line:84%
absolutely preclude that he
could have been conscious

01:04:50.590 --> 01:04:54.730 align:middle line:84%
by the standard
neurophysiological theories

01:04:54.730 --> 01:04:56.100 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness.

01:04:56.100 --> 01:04:59.420 align:middle line:84%
But when he woke up,
he talked about going

01:04:59.420 --> 01:05:04.360 align:middle line:84%
into this other world, and
just an incredible story

01:05:04.360 --> 01:05:06.960 align:middle line:90%
of a journey into another world.

01:05:06.960 --> 01:05:10.960 align:middle line:84%
And throughout this, he
kept seeing this young woman

01:05:10.960 --> 01:05:14.110 align:middle line:84%
that he didn't know who she
was, but she was at a distance

01:05:14.110 --> 01:05:17.090 align:middle line:90%
and not making direct contact.

01:05:17.090 --> 01:05:19.830 align:middle line:84%
But he kept seeing
this young woman.

01:05:19.830 --> 01:05:23.740 align:middle line:84%
Now, after he recovered from
this illness with no seqhela,

01:05:23.740 --> 01:05:26.120 align:middle line:90%
he's just vibrant.

01:05:26.120 --> 01:05:29.180 align:middle line:84%
And so he started being
curious about his--

01:05:29.180 --> 01:05:32.820 align:middle line:84%
he had known that he was
adopted at age four months,

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:39.230 align:middle line:84%
and adopted by a neurosurgeon in
Winston-Salem, North Carolina,

01:05:39.230 --> 01:05:41.150 align:middle line:90%
where Eben grew up.

01:05:41.150 --> 01:05:45.980 align:middle line:84%
And so he knew that he had
been adopted at four months,

01:05:45.980 --> 01:05:48.110 align:middle line:84%
and what he had been
told or understood

01:05:48.110 --> 01:05:51.180 align:middle line:84%
about his birth parents was
that they were high school

01:05:51.180 --> 01:05:53.860 align:middle line:84%
sweethearts and that
after he was born

01:05:53.860 --> 01:05:56.430 align:middle line:90%
they went their separate ways.

01:05:56.430 --> 01:05:59.890 align:middle line:84%
So then he got curious when he
came back from his experience

01:05:59.890 --> 01:06:05.100 align:middle line:84%
as to what-- you know, about
his biological birth situation.

01:06:05.100 --> 01:06:07.480 align:middle line:84%
So he did some inquiring,
and he found out

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:10.850 align:middle line:84%
that this woman who
worked at the institution

01:06:10.850 --> 01:06:14.550 align:middle line:84%
where he was born was willing
to give him some information.

01:06:14.550 --> 01:06:18.800 align:middle line:84%
And he found out that his birth
parents had subsequently gotten

01:06:18.800 --> 01:06:22.040 align:middle line:84%
married and had
several children.

01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:24.730 align:middle line:84%
So he went and made
the reunion with them,

01:06:24.730 --> 01:06:28.270 align:middle line:84%
and when he did--
he found them--

01:06:28.270 --> 01:06:32.060 align:middle line:84%
they were in mourning because
of the loss of their daughter.

01:06:32.060 --> 01:06:36.160 align:middle line:84%
And so when Eben saw the
photograph of this daughter,

01:06:36.160 --> 01:06:40.800 align:middle line:84%
it was the young girl he
had seen in this vision.

01:06:40.800 --> 01:06:42.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Wow, that's
a chilling story.

01:06:42.670 --> 01:06:46.240 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: This is coming out
soon, I think, in a book.

01:06:46.240 --> 01:06:49.080 align:middle line:84%
And this, I think,
is very difficult

01:06:49.080 --> 01:06:51.570 align:middle line:90%
to explain in prosaic terms.

01:06:51.570 --> 01:06:55.540 align:middle line:84%
I think we're getting closer and
closer to the situation where

01:06:55.540 --> 01:06:58.850 align:middle line:84%
we're just going to have
to breathe a deep sigh

01:06:58.850 --> 01:07:01.680 align:middle line:84%
and say, my god, there
is life after death.

01:07:01.680 --> 01:07:03.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's what
you're here for.

01:07:03.420 --> 01:07:05.950 align:middle line:84%
Tell me a little bit about
your new book, "Paranormal."

01:07:05.950 --> 01:07:08.510 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, "The
Paranormal" is my memoirs.

01:07:08.510 --> 01:07:14.760 align:middle line:84%
And this sort of suggestion came
from my co-writer Paul Perry.

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:17.180 align:middle line:84%
And I never thought
my life would

01:07:17.180 --> 01:07:18.520 align:middle line:90%
be particularly interesting.

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:19.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

01:07:19.530 --> 01:07:20.585 align:middle line:90%
That's why you're here.

01:07:20.585 --> 01:07:23.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: But my wonderful
friend, Paul Perry,

01:07:23.040 --> 01:07:28.830 align:middle line:84%
who's just a superb journalist
plus a really nice guy--

01:07:28.830 --> 01:07:32.940 align:middle line:84%
and he-- I've known
Paul since 1988.

01:07:32.940 --> 01:07:36.960 align:middle line:84%
And so he-- I sort of
told my life story to him,

01:07:36.960 --> 01:07:40.440 align:middle line:84%
and then he's put it
together in this book.

01:07:40.440 --> 01:07:43.740 align:middle line:84%
And it's about the quest
I've made in my life

01:07:43.740 --> 01:07:46.470 align:middle line:84%
to try to understand
this mystery of what

01:07:46.470 --> 01:07:48.382 align:middle line:90%
happens to us when we die.

01:07:48.382 --> 01:07:50.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, there
was also a movie that

01:07:50.090 --> 01:07:53.080 align:middle line:84%
was made about this experience
of the near-death experience

01:07:53.080 --> 01:07:53.830 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

01:07:53.830 --> 01:07:55.730 align:middle line:84%
We have a clip of
the movie coming up

01:07:55.730 --> 01:07:59.630 align:middle line:84%
that kind of encapsulates what
people experience when they

01:07:59.630 --> 01:08:01.140 align:middle line:84%
go through a
near-death experience.

01:08:01.140 --> 01:08:04.230 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at that.

01:08:04.230 --> 01:08:07.520 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:08:07.520 --> 01:08:15.480 align:middle line:90%


01:08:15.480 --> 01:08:18.770 align:middle line:84%
>>The lightning came down the
phone line, entered my neck.

01:08:18.770 --> 01:08:22.240 align:middle line:84%
It went through my spine,
threw me up in the air.

01:08:22.240 --> 01:08:25.399 align:middle line:84%
>>And I felt myself
pop out of the body.

01:08:25.399 --> 01:08:27.960 align:middle line:84%
Then I felt myself
float up to the ceiling.

01:08:27.960 --> 01:08:30.630 align:middle line:84%
And the doctor and the
nurse were in there,

01:08:30.630 --> 01:08:32.158 align:middle line:90%
and he was looking at me.

01:08:32.158 --> 01:08:33.204 align:middle line:90%
He said, she's gone.

01:08:33.204 --> 01:08:34.880 align:middle line:90%
She's dead.

01:08:34.880 --> 01:08:38.450 align:middle line:90%
>>And I was taken to hospital.

01:08:38.450 --> 01:08:42.460 align:middle line:84%
Doctors did anything
they could to help me,

01:08:42.460 --> 01:08:46.430 align:middle line:90%
but I was declared dead.

01:08:46.430 --> 01:08:48.609 align:middle line:84%
>>I realized I
was out of my body

01:08:48.609 --> 01:08:52.037 align:middle line:84%
when I was suddenly
looking at this light.

01:08:52.037 --> 01:08:54.120 align:middle line:84%
>>Out of that light stepped
the most amazing being

01:08:54.120 --> 01:08:56.170 align:middle line:84%
I have ever been
in the presence of.

01:08:56.170 --> 01:08:59.895 align:middle line:84%
>>It was just all-consuming
love, wonderful love.

01:08:59.895 --> 01:09:41.950 align:middle line:90%


01:09:41.950 --> 01:09:44.088 align:middle line:84%
>>Death is nothing more
or less than a doorway,

01:09:44.088 --> 01:09:45.430 align:middle line:90%
something you walk through.

01:09:45.430 --> 01:09:47.359 align:middle line:90%
>>Death does not exist.

01:09:47.359 --> 01:09:48.174 align:middle line:90%
Don't be afraid.

01:09:48.174 --> 01:10:12.360 align:middle line:90%


01:10:12.360 --> 01:10:16.905 align:middle line:84%
>>This was holographical view
of being inside of your life

01:10:16.905 --> 01:10:20.970 align:middle line:84%
and then being as a
viewer, participating

01:10:20.970 --> 01:10:22.870 align:middle line:90%
the play of theater.

01:10:22.870 --> 01:10:41.000 align:middle line:90%


01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:42.980 align:middle line:84%
>>He was asking
me, had I learned

01:10:42.980 --> 01:10:45.840 align:middle line:84%
to love my fellow human
beings the way that he totally

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:47.676 align:middle line:90%
accepted and loved me?

01:10:47.676 --> 01:11:13.260 align:middle line:90%


01:11:13.260 --> 01:11:14.244 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:11:14.244 --> 01:11:17.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It really, really
does answer so many-- well,

01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:19.544 align:middle line:90%
it poses so many questions.

01:11:19.544 --> 01:11:20.460 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: There you go.

01:11:20.460 --> 01:11:21.001 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:11:21.001 --> 01:11:23.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You come up
with your own answers.

01:11:23.170 --> 01:11:26.780 align:middle line:84%
What do you think is the overall
thing that people take away

01:11:26.780 --> 01:11:32.560 align:middle line:84%
from an experience
like nearly dying?

01:11:32.560 --> 01:11:35.270 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: That the
most important thing

01:11:35.270 --> 01:11:40.680 align:middle line:84%
we can do while we're here
is to learn how to love,

01:11:40.680 --> 01:11:43.520 align:middle line:84%
and that that's a difficult
thing even after you've

01:11:43.520 --> 01:11:47.120 align:middle line:84%
had this vision, but
that it's worth pursuing.

01:11:47.120 --> 01:11:50.120 align:middle line:84%
And that's what I hear from
people all over the world,

01:11:50.120 --> 01:11:55.310 align:middle line:84%
that what this is all
about is learning to love.

01:11:55.310 --> 01:11:57.995 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, this
particular time, though,

01:11:57.995 --> 01:11:59.890 align:middle line:84%
in history that
we're in right now,

01:11:59.890 --> 01:12:03.607 align:middle line:84%
why do you think that is
so apparent right now?

01:12:03.607 --> 01:12:04.940 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Well, it's interesting.

01:12:04.940 --> 01:12:06.950 align:middle line:84%
There have always been
these experiences,

01:12:06.950 --> 01:12:09.810 align:middle line:84%
and they were discussed
about in antiquity,

01:12:09.810 --> 01:12:12.880 align:middle line:84%
but the reason why we're
hearing so many these days,

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:15.530 align:middle line:84%
I conjecture, is
that the techniques

01:12:15.530 --> 01:12:20.470 align:middle line:84%
of cardiopulmonary resuscitation
are refined to such an extent

01:12:20.470 --> 01:12:23.220 align:middle line:84%
that we can bring a
lot more people back.

01:12:23.220 --> 01:12:27.950 align:middle line:84%
And I think that-- I don't
want to draw a connection here,

01:12:27.950 --> 01:12:30.980 align:middle line:84%
but, I mean, to me it's a
rather remarkable coincidence

01:12:30.980 --> 01:12:36.130 align:middle line:84%
that just at the time
where this is surfacing

01:12:36.130 --> 01:12:40.990 align:middle line:84%
as an undeniable thing-- we're
really into a situation now

01:12:40.990 --> 01:12:44.730 align:middle line:84%
where we can't turn away
from these experiences.

01:12:44.730 --> 01:12:47.560 align:middle line:90%
This is a reality.

01:12:47.560 --> 01:12:50.930 align:middle line:84%
And at that same time,
it looks like we're

01:12:50.930 --> 01:12:53.420 align:middle line:84%
in a race with
ourselves to see who

01:12:53.420 --> 01:12:57.390 align:middle line:90%
can destroy the planet first.

01:12:57.390 --> 01:12:58.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's
a paradox here.

01:12:58.860 --> 01:12:59.510 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: I do.

01:12:59.510 --> 01:13:00.010 align:middle line:90%
I do.

01:13:00.010 --> 01:13:03.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think that people
have always said, oh, times

01:13:03.220 --> 01:13:07.650 align:middle line:84%
are bad and so on, but we have a
different kind of evidence now.

01:13:07.650 --> 01:13:09.090 align:middle line:84%
All the many things
that are going

01:13:09.090 --> 01:13:13.660 align:middle line:84%
on-- the trouble with the
atmosphere, the climate

01:13:13.660 --> 01:13:19.220 align:middle line:84%
change, the proliferation
of nuclear weapons,

01:13:19.220 --> 01:13:23.390 align:middle line:84%
the real chance that terrorists
will get a nuclear bomb

01:13:23.390 --> 01:13:28.620 align:middle line:84%
and strike at a city-- all of
these things are pretty grim.

01:13:28.620 --> 01:13:32.090 align:middle line:84%
Plus, I think personally-- and
this is like being on a soapbox

01:13:32.090 --> 01:13:34.790 align:middle line:84%
to some degree,
but we've developed

01:13:34.790 --> 01:13:39.200 align:middle line:84%
a society here in America of
the immediate-gratification

01:13:39.200 --> 01:13:42.220 align:middle line:84%
mentality, that
people want it now.

01:13:42.220 --> 01:13:43.680 align:middle line:90%
They want it without effort.

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:47.050 align:middle line:84%
They want it without
going through a process.

01:13:47.050 --> 01:13:49.210 align:middle line:84%
So it looks to me that
all of these things

01:13:49.210 --> 01:13:52.200 align:middle line:84%
are coming together
in a way that people

01:13:52.200 --> 01:13:53.320 align:middle line:90%
are kind of desperate.

01:13:53.320 --> 01:13:56.030 align:middle line:84%
They're wandering
around without a center.

01:13:56.030 --> 01:13:58.455 align:middle line:84%
And they're wondering,
what's this all about?

01:13:58.455 --> 01:14:01.780 align:middle line:84%
And there's very scary
things going on in the world

01:14:01.780 --> 01:14:03.000 align:middle line:90%
right now.

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.760 align:middle line:84%
So I think this
information can be

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:08.980 align:middle line:90%
very comforting in that context.

01:14:08.980 --> 01:14:10.600 align:middle line:84%
The way I've come
to think of it,

01:14:10.600 --> 01:14:14.890 align:middle line:84%
Lisa, is-- and I'm speaking
kind of metaphorically here

01:14:14.890 --> 01:14:17.890 align:middle line:84%
admittedly-- but I think
this thing we're in

01:14:17.890 --> 01:14:21.419 align:middle line:84%
is God's educate and
entertainment medium.

01:14:21.419 --> 01:14:22.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, what do you mean?

01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:26.670 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, I mean I think
God is totally in charge here.

01:14:26.670 --> 01:14:28.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Coming from a
non-religious person.

01:14:28.860 --> 01:14:31.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yeah, well,
I'm still not religious.

01:14:31.810 --> 01:14:33.870 align:middle line:84%
I talk to God all the
time, and he's never

01:14:33.870 --> 01:14:37.460 align:middle line:84%
said to me about going to
church or anything like that.

01:14:37.460 --> 01:14:39.915 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But what do you
mean, specifically what

01:14:39.915 --> 01:14:41.160 align:middle line:90%
you were talking about?

01:14:41.160 --> 01:14:45.970 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, I do think
that this life we're

01:14:45.970 --> 01:14:51.440 align:middle line:84%
in, that the explanation
of it lies outside of it.

01:14:51.440 --> 01:14:54.060 align:middle line:84%
And the way that I
sort of put it together

01:14:54.060 --> 01:14:58.110 align:middle line:84%
is that we're here in this
dimension and this kind

01:14:58.110 --> 01:15:02.820 align:middle line:84%
of physical framework
as participants

01:15:02.820 --> 01:15:06.730 align:middle line:84%
analogously to people
in a play or a drama.

01:15:06.730 --> 01:15:10.030 align:middle line:84%
I think one of the people
in that documentary

01:15:10.030 --> 01:15:11.220 align:middle line:90%
mentioned that.

01:15:11.220 --> 01:15:14.150 align:middle line:84%
And that's, incidentally,
a point of view

01:15:14.150 --> 01:15:18.430 align:middle line:84%
that's in Hinduism, that
this is a large play.

01:15:18.430 --> 01:15:21.660 align:middle line:90%


01:15:21.660 --> 01:15:24.690 align:middle line:84%
Shakespeare, I think,
said something similar,

01:15:24.690 --> 01:15:26.260 align:middle line:90%
like that all life is a stage.

01:15:26.260 --> 01:15:28.980 align:middle line:90%


01:15:28.980 --> 01:15:33.810 align:middle line:84%
And what I think we're here
for is to learn and also

01:15:33.810 --> 01:15:37.550 align:middle line:84%
to become more
loving, to develop--

01:15:37.550 --> 01:15:42.010 align:middle line:84%
learn how to love and to
develop loving relationships

01:15:42.010 --> 01:15:43.000 align:middle line:90%
with others.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:46.970 align:middle line:84%
And I think, to sort
of transcend ego.

01:15:46.970 --> 01:15:49.540 align:middle line:84%
Ego equals pain, as
far as I can tell.

01:15:49.540 --> 01:15:51.450 align:middle line:84%
That's one of the
few things that I've

01:15:51.450 --> 01:15:53.710 align:middle line:84%
learned as a person
who's studied

01:15:53.710 --> 01:15:57.810 align:middle line:84%
the mind is, that much
I'm sure of, ego is pain.

01:15:57.810 --> 01:15:59.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To one person
or the other, yes.

01:15:59.810 --> 01:16:01.530 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: It's always pain.

01:16:01.530 --> 01:16:03.370 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You mentioned
to me earlier

01:16:03.370 --> 01:16:06.510 align:middle line:90%
that you live an ego-less life.

01:16:06.510 --> 01:16:08.310 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, and
that itself sounds

01:16:08.310 --> 01:16:11.390 align:middle line:90%
like an egotistical statement.

01:16:11.390 --> 01:16:14.640 align:middle line:84%
Which it would be if I said,
well, the way I've gotten

01:16:14.640 --> 01:16:17.330 align:middle line:84%
finished with the ego is that
I went up on the mountain

01:16:17.330 --> 01:16:20.710 align:middle line:84%
and I did the chants, but
that's not how I did it.

01:16:20.710 --> 01:16:23.050 align:middle line:84%
The reason I'm
finished with the ego

01:16:23.050 --> 01:16:26.100 align:middle line:84%
is that I pretty near
killed myself with it.

01:16:26.100 --> 01:16:29.980 align:middle line:84%
And my particular ego
trip was jealousy.

01:16:29.980 --> 01:16:33.530 align:middle line:84%
But once you go
through an ego trip,

01:16:33.530 --> 01:16:37.720 align:middle line:84%
you kind of realize that
all ego trips are the same.

01:16:37.720 --> 01:16:40.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Jealousy, control--
all of it's the same thing.

01:16:40.160 --> 01:16:40.980 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Exactly.

01:16:40.980 --> 01:16:44.390 align:middle line:84%
And that, I'm sick
of myself in a way.

01:16:44.390 --> 01:16:46.480 align:middle line:90%
I'm through with Raymond Moody.

01:16:46.480 --> 01:16:52.190 align:middle line:84%
And part of this is just being
67 years old, because as people

01:16:52.190 --> 01:16:55.440 align:middle line:84%
grow older we kind of
surrender these things.

01:16:55.440 --> 01:16:58.990 align:middle line:84%
And I think, like many
people in my age range,

01:16:58.990 --> 01:17:00.870 align:middle line:84%
I don't think about
myself anymore.

01:17:00.870 --> 01:17:03.750 align:middle line:84%
I think about--
what I want to do

01:17:03.750 --> 01:17:08.070 align:middle line:84%
is try to help the
generations that are coming,

01:17:08.070 --> 01:17:10.280 align:middle line:90%
especially my kids.

01:17:10.280 --> 01:17:12.840 align:middle line:84%
And of course, my kids
will be in a world

01:17:12.840 --> 01:17:14.800 align:middle line:84%
where there are other
people their age.

01:17:14.800 --> 01:17:16.690 align:middle line:90%
So I really do.

01:17:16.690 --> 01:17:18.950 align:middle line:84%
I'm in this situation where,
like many other people

01:17:18.950 --> 01:17:22.950 align:middle line:84%
in my age, I'm just-- I want to
try to help smooth things over

01:17:22.950 --> 01:17:24.750 align:middle line:90%
for the people who are coming.

01:17:24.750 --> 01:17:26.300 align:middle line:90%
I still enjoy myself, too.

01:17:26.300 --> 01:17:28.107 align:middle line:90%
Don't get me wrong.

01:17:28.107 --> 01:17:29.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What type
of message would you

01:17:29.690 --> 01:17:32.990 align:middle line:90%
give the youth of today?

01:17:32.990 --> 01:17:35.700 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, one thing I would
say very severely, I mean now,

01:17:35.700 --> 01:17:38.140 align:middle line:84%
youth, the way it's
set up, they don't

01:17:38.140 --> 01:17:40.480 align:middle line:84%
suppose to listen to
their elders, right,

01:17:40.480 --> 01:17:42.750 align:middle line:84%
and they got to learn
it for themselves.

01:17:42.750 --> 01:17:46.610 align:middle line:84%
But time's kind of running
out in a way for this society.

01:17:46.610 --> 01:17:52.220 align:middle line:84%
What I think more than anything
else we need to do is to,

01:17:52.220 --> 01:17:56.800 align:middle line:84%
number one, get over this
instant gratification

01:17:56.800 --> 01:17:58.600 align:middle line:90%
mentality.

01:17:58.600 --> 01:18:02.587 align:middle line:84%
Immediate gratification is
no gratification at all.

01:18:02.587 --> 01:18:04.295 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, with
the age of technology,

01:18:04.295 --> 01:18:07.900 align:middle line:84%
it does-- it really puts
people into that space.

01:18:07.900 --> 01:18:10.780 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yes, and
there is a great value

01:18:10.780 --> 01:18:13.360 align:middle line:90%
in working through a process.

01:18:13.360 --> 01:18:15.040 align:middle line:84%
Then the second
thing I would say

01:18:15.040 --> 01:18:18.560 align:middle line:84%
is that we've really got
to wake up to the fact

01:18:18.560 --> 01:18:20.550 align:middle line:84%
that this information
about near-death

01:18:20.550 --> 01:18:25.080 align:middle line:84%
experiences as getting
harder, and harder, and harder

01:18:25.080 --> 01:18:29.730 align:middle line:84%
to dismiss or to say that,
well, this is the brain damage

01:18:29.730 --> 01:18:32.400 align:middle line:90%
or whatever, because it's not.

01:18:32.400 --> 01:18:37.020 align:middle line:84%
If the bystanders have the same
experience as the people who

01:18:37.020 --> 01:18:41.040 align:middle line:84%
are-- who almost die
and return, then it's

01:18:41.040 --> 01:18:44.010 align:middle line:84%
not the oxygen
deprivation to the brain.

01:18:44.010 --> 01:18:45.832 align:middle line:90%
Something else is going on.

01:18:45.832 --> 01:18:47.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The shared
death experience

01:18:47.290 --> 01:18:48.110 align:middle line:90%
really shows that, yes.

01:18:48.110 --> 01:18:49.026 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: That's right.

01:18:49.026 --> 01:18:51.140 align:middle line:84%
And then the third
thing, which comes

01:18:51.140 --> 01:18:55.590 align:middle line:84%
from the near-death experience
and so on and these shared

01:18:55.590 --> 01:18:58.990 align:middle line:84%
death experiences, is that
what this is all about

01:18:58.990 --> 01:19:01.140 align:middle line:90%
is learning how to love.

01:19:01.140 --> 01:19:06.140 align:middle line:84%
And to get engrossed in the
ideology of your religion

01:19:06.140 --> 01:19:11.460 align:middle line:84%
or whatever is
counterproductive to this.

01:19:11.460 --> 01:19:14.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But what if your
religion's ideology is to love?

01:19:14.220 --> 01:19:14.970 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yeah.

01:19:14.970 --> 01:19:17.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's what I mean
is-- but let's face it.

01:19:17.760 --> 01:19:21.520 align:middle line:84%
On TV, we see a lot of
people who aren't so loving.

01:19:21.520 --> 01:19:24.960 align:middle line:84%
I saw Franklin
Graham on CNN today,

01:19:24.960 --> 01:19:27.850 align:middle line:84%
and I thought that was a
very mean-spirited person,

01:19:27.850 --> 01:19:29.190 align:middle line:90%
to tell you the truth.

01:19:29.190 --> 01:19:33.730 align:middle line:84%
Like he's got the insight
into Jesus, and the rest of us

01:19:33.730 --> 01:19:34.760 align:middle line:90%
are scum.

01:19:34.760 --> 01:19:36.020 align:middle line:90%
Well, no.

01:19:36.020 --> 01:19:36.910 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:19:36.910 --> 01:19:40.700 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have anything to do
with what religious ideology

01:19:40.700 --> 01:19:42.270 align:middle line:90%
you subscribe to.

01:19:42.270 --> 01:19:44.830 align:middle line:84%
It has to do with the
kind of life you lead

01:19:44.830 --> 01:19:49.289 align:middle line:84%
and having to-- to try to
be loving to other people.

01:19:49.289 --> 01:19:51.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, there is one
last clip that we have here,

01:19:51.580 --> 01:19:54.930 align:middle line:84%
and it kind of sums up Raymond
Moody's experience here

01:19:54.930 --> 01:19:57.217 align:middle line:84%
of what he wants to
impart upon people

01:19:57.217 --> 01:19:58.550 align:middle line:90%
about the near-death experience.

01:19:58.550 --> 01:20:00.968 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look at that.

01:20:00.968 --> 01:20:02.456 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:20:02.456 --> 01:20:05.432 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: My hope for it
is that it will turn out

01:20:05.432 --> 01:20:07.420 align:middle line:84%
to be something
very therapeutic,

01:20:07.420 --> 01:20:10.250 align:middle line:84%
and that it will help
people who are undergoing

01:20:10.250 --> 01:20:15.189 align:middle line:84%
prolonged grief, who just can't
let go of a loved one lost

01:20:15.189 --> 01:20:20.704 align:middle line:84%
to death and for that reason
are miserable themselves.

01:20:20.704 --> 01:20:22.770 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
most common things

01:20:22.770 --> 01:20:24.750 align:middle line:84%
that you hear people
say at that time

01:20:24.750 --> 01:20:29.590 align:middle line:84%
is, if I only had
five more minutes.

01:20:29.590 --> 01:20:33.140 align:middle line:84%
What we can do now,
without a doubt,

01:20:33.140 --> 01:20:39.380 align:middle line:84%
is that we can give people
that five more minutes.

01:20:39.380 --> 01:20:45.300 align:middle line:84%
If we can help people like
this turn themselves around

01:20:45.300 --> 01:20:51.120 align:middle line:84%
and open up to hope and to a new
life, then I think all of this

01:20:51.120 --> 01:20:52.575 align:middle line:90%
would be justified.

01:20:52.575 --> 01:20:53.927 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:20:53.927 --> 01:20:56.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's so much
more that you have to say.

01:20:56.010 --> 01:21:00.100 align:middle line:84%
We were just talking about--
about what you could--

01:21:00.100 --> 01:21:02.920 align:middle line:84%
What do you want to just
conclude with and tell us?

01:21:02.920 --> 01:21:03.950 align:middle line:90%
What's next for you?

01:21:03.950 --> 01:21:05.990 align:middle line:84%
I have so much-- You
have so much more to say.

01:21:05.990 --> 01:21:06.992 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:21:06.992 --> 01:21:09.450 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, first of all,
what I'd like to say to people

01:21:09.450 --> 01:21:12.900 align:middle line:84%
is, when you hear
these people on TV

01:21:12.900 --> 01:21:15.220 align:middle line:84%
who are very nice
and well meaning,

01:21:15.220 --> 01:21:19.500 align:middle line:84%
who have a Ph.D. or an
M.D. behind their names,

01:21:19.500 --> 01:21:22.650 align:middle line:84%
and they're saying things
like, oh, we can scientifically

01:21:22.650 --> 01:21:26.380 align:middle line:84%
prove that there's life
after death, watch out.

01:21:26.380 --> 01:21:27.580 align:middle line:90%
I know some of these people.

01:21:27.580 --> 01:21:28.490 align:middle line:90%
They're very sweet.

01:21:28.490 --> 01:21:31.510 align:middle line:84%
They're well meaning, but
they have practically zero

01:21:31.510 --> 01:21:33.260 align:middle line:90%
critical thinking skills.

01:21:33.260 --> 01:21:34.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

01:21:34.160 --> 01:21:37.410 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: The question of
life after death is not yet

01:21:37.410 --> 01:21:39.105 align:middle line:90%
a scientific question.

01:21:39.105 --> 01:21:41.550 align:middle line:90%
That's the fact.

01:21:41.550 --> 01:21:43.870 align:middle line:84%
Because what we've
done in the West

01:21:43.870 --> 01:21:48.470 align:middle line:84%
is that we've made a kind
of God out of science.

01:21:48.470 --> 01:21:51.050 align:middle line:84%
And the fact is
that science is not

01:21:51.050 --> 01:21:54.090 align:middle line:90%
going to solve all our problems.

01:21:54.090 --> 01:21:57.120 align:middle line:84%
So TO-- at this point
in the 21st century,

01:21:57.120 --> 01:21:59.910 align:middle line:84%
to try to imply to
people that this

01:21:59.910 --> 01:22:05.180 align:middle line:84%
can be a scientific
question is not valid.

01:22:05.180 --> 01:22:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And that mistake sort of
casts dispersions there

01:22:09.240 --> 01:22:13.350 align:middle line:84%
on all of us who investigate
near-death experiences.

01:22:13.350 --> 01:22:16.690 align:middle line:84%
What I want to say
is that we are now

01:22:16.690 --> 01:22:22.390 align:middle line:84%
very close to having
entirely new rational means

01:22:22.390 --> 01:22:26.380 align:middle line:84%
of investigating this
question that are going to be,

01:22:26.380 --> 01:22:28.649 align:middle line:90%
when this comes out, astounding.

01:22:28.649 --> 01:22:29.940 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, what do you mean?

01:22:29.940 --> 01:22:32.930 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, what I mean is
that the real question when

01:22:32.930 --> 01:22:35.040 align:middle line:84%
we-- and there's
a big difference

01:22:35.040 --> 01:22:38.370 align:middle line:90%
between rational and scientific.

01:22:38.370 --> 01:22:42.670 align:middle line:84%
Rational is a larger
category than scientific.

01:22:42.670 --> 01:22:47.140 align:middle line:84%
One category of reason
is scientific inquiry,

01:22:47.140 --> 01:22:51.520 align:middle line:84%
but scientific inquiry is
only about 400 years old.

01:22:51.520 --> 01:22:55.530 align:middle line:84%
We've had reason for a
much longer period of time.

01:22:55.530 --> 01:22:59.330 align:middle line:84%
And the real
difficulty in thinking

01:22:59.330 --> 01:23:03.300 align:middle line:84%
about the possibility of a
rational proof of an afterlife

01:23:03.300 --> 01:23:07.790 align:middle line:84%
was best stated by a wonderful
thinker named David Hume.

01:23:07.790 --> 01:23:13.410 align:middle line:84%
And to date him for you, he
was a friend of Ben Franklin's.

01:23:13.410 --> 01:23:17.730 align:middle line:90%
Hume lived from 1711 to 1776.

01:23:17.730 --> 01:23:21.260 align:middle line:84%
He's well known as one of the
people who was kind of got

01:23:21.260 --> 01:23:23.980 align:middle line:90%
scientific thinking on its feet.

01:23:23.980 --> 01:23:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And he made some
brilliant insights

01:23:26.760 --> 01:23:29.970 align:middle line:84%
into inductive logic,
which scientists use,

01:23:29.970 --> 01:23:33.390 align:middle line:84%
and also into the
notion of causality

01:23:33.390 --> 01:23:34.910 align:middle line:90%
that we have in science.

01:23:34.910 --> 01:23:39.510 align:middle line:84%
And Hume said more succinctly
than anybody else ever said,

01:23:39.510 --> 01:23:43.070 align:middle line:84%
he pointed out the
real difficulty

01:23:43.070 --> 01:23:48.210 align:middle line:84%
in investigating this question
of life after death rationally.

01:23:48.210 --> 01:23:52.540 align:middle line:84%
And what Hume said was, "by
the mere light of reason,

01:23:52.540 --> 01:23:57.880 align:middle line:84%
it seems difficult to prove
the immortality of the soul."

01:23:57.880 --> 01:24:01.780 align:middle line:84%
Then he went on to say,
"some new species of logic

01:24:01.780 --> 01:24:05.880 align:middle line:84%
is requisite for that purpose,
and some new faculties

01:24:05.880 --> 01:24:11.760 align:middle line:84%
of the mind that they may enable
us to comprehend that logic."

01:24:11.760 --> 01:24:15.440 align:middle line:84%
Now, for a long time,
that has been regarded

01:24:15.440 --> 01:24:17.800 align:middle line:84%
as a sort of ironical
statement and that

01:24:17.800 --> 01:24:21.120 align:middle line:84%
really what he was getting
at is that it's impossible.

01:24:21.120 --> 01:24:24.370 align:middle line:84%
Because the logic that we've
inherited from Aristotle

01:24:24.370 --> 01:24:27.530 align:middle line:84%
has served us well
for 2,300 years.

01:24:27.530 --> 01:24:29.350 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it doesn't
seem very likely

01:24:29.350 --> 01:24:32.610 align:middle line:84%
that we could come up with
a new system of logic.

01:24:32.610 --> 01:24:35.510 align:middle line:84%
And also we think we know
our minds pretty well,

01:24:35.510 --> 01:24:38.005 align:middle line:84%
so the idea that there could
be these hidden faculties

01:24:38.005 --> 01:24:41.330 align:middle line:90%
of the mind seems implausible.

01:24:41.330 --> 01:24:44.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, what I am just perfectly
confident in sitting here

01:24:44.390 --> 01:24:48.830 align:middle line:84%
and saying to you is that
problem has now been solved.

01:24:48.830 --> 01:24:52.370 align:middle line:84%
We do have a new
system of logic,

01:24:52.370 --> 01:24:54.910 align:middle line:84%
not to replace
Aristotle's logic,

01:24:54.910 --> 01:24:58.910 align:middle line:84%
but to supplement it in
these areas which heretofore

01:24:58.910 --> 01:25:04.100 align:middle line:84%
have fallen outside of
the process of logic.

01:25:04.100 --> 01:25:07.450 align:middle line:84%
And through this, we
find that we can actually

01:25:07.450 --> 01:25:10.430 align:middle line:84%
open up these hidden
faculties of the mind

01:25:10.430 --> 01:25:13.110 align:middle line:90%
that we didn't know we had.

01:25:13.110 --> 01:25:16.574 align:middle line:84%
And what this-- the
implication of this is

01:25:16.574 --> 01:25:22.490 align:middle line:84%
is that this results in entirely
new ways of genuinely rational

01:25:22.490 --> 01:25:25.780 align:middle line:84%
investigation of this
question of life after death.

01:25:25.780 --> 01:25:30.380 align:middle line:84%
And what we are
doing now, we are

01:25:30.380 --> 01:25:34.060 align:middle line:84%
people who are learning
this new logic.

01:25:34.060 --> 01:25:37.410 align:middle line:84%
When, just by chance
in the future,

01:25:37.410 --> 01:25:40.550 align:middle line:84%
they happen to have a
near-death experience,

01:25:40.550 --> 01:25:43.630 align:middle line:84%
will be able to come back
and talk about it to us

01:25:43.630 --> 01:25:45.450 align:middle line:90%
in an entirely new way.

01:25:45.450 --> 01:25:48.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What is this new
logic you're talking about?

01:25:48.390 --> 01:25:51.360 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well,
basically the difficulty

01:25:51.360 --> 01:25:55.840 align:middle line:84%
with the notion of life after
death from the point of view

01:25:55.840 --> 01:25:59.650 align:middle line:84%
of regular logic is that
it's a self-contradiction.

01:25:59.650 --> 01:26:01.700 align:middle line:84%
When you say, there
is life after death,

01:26:01.700 --> 01:26:03.960 align:middle line:84%
if you look up the meanings
of those words, that's

01:26:03.960 --> 01:26:06.360 align:middle line:84%
an outright
self-contradiction, and it

01:26:06.360 --> 01:26:09.310 align:middle line:84%
doesn't fit into
Aristotelian logic.

01:26:09.310 --> 01:26:12.890 align:middle line:84%
What we now have is
a new kind of logic

01:26:12.890 --> 01:26:15.070 align:middle line:84%
that helps us
comprehend things that

01:26:15.070 --> 01:26:18.900 align:middle line:84%
are unintelligible from the
point of view of regular logic.

01:26:18.900 --> 01:26:22.320 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm completely
confident in sitting here

01:26:22.320 --> 01:26:26.310 align:middle line:84%
and saying to you is that now
we have, in effect, a logic

01:26:26.310 --> 01:26:28.280 align:middle line:90%
of the unintelligible.

01:26:28.280 --> 01:26:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And when people know this
logic of the unintelligible

01:26:32.450 --> 01:26:35.442 align:middle line:84%
and then subsequently they
have a near-death experience,

01:26:35.442 --> 01:26:36.900 align:middle line:84%
they're going to
come back and they

01:26:36.900 --> 01:26:39.820 align:middle line:84%
won't have the same
difficulty that people

01:26:39.820 --> 01:26:42.822 align:middle line:84%
have had of putting it
into words because they

01:26:42.822 --> 01:26:44.030 align:middle line:90%
have a new logical framework.

01:26:44.030 --> 01:26:44.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

01:26:44.620 --> 01:26:45.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:26:45.300 --> 01:26:48.640 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: And this is
already bearing some fruit.

01:26:48.640 --> 01:26:53.700 align:middle line:84%
So stay tuned, because in
the not-too-distant future,

01:26:53.700 --> 01:26:57.630 align:middle line:84%
we are going to have--
well, I'll put it this way.

01:26:57.630 --> 01:27:05.400 align:middle line:84%
There has now been a solid
step of genuine progress

01:27:05.400 --> 01:27:08.960 align:middle line:84%
toward the rational
comprehension of the biggest

01:27:08.960 --> 01:27:10.760 align:middle line:90%
mystery of human existence.

01:27:10.760 --> 01:27:14.130 align:middle line:84%
That is, the question
of life after death.

01:27:14.130 --> 01:27:17.340 align:middle line:84%
So we are now into
an era where we're

01:27:17.340 --> 01:27:23.350 align:middle line:84%
going to have new means of
investigating this and entirely

01:27:23.350 --> 01:27:27.700 align:middle line:84%
unique methods that have never
been done before where we will

01:27:27.700 --> 01:27:34.969 align:middle line:84%
actually be able to track people
right as they cross over--

01:27:34.969 --> 01:27:37.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You have to tell me what
some of those new means are.

01:27:37.510 --> 01:27:39.218 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure you're at
the forefront of this.

01:27:39.218 --> 01:27:41.510 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Well, one
is that we have

01:27:41.510 --> 01:27:46.840 align:middle line:84%
a way now where-- have you-- one
thing that may sound startling

01:27:46.840 --> 01:27:50.880 align:middle line:84%
but that many of our viewers
will be able to relate to is

01:27:50.880 --> 01:27:54.590 align:middle line:84%
that its a very common
phenomenon that,

01:27:54.590 --> 01:27:56.970 align:middle line:84%
as people are in their
final stage of dying,

01:27:56.970 --> 01:28:01.290 align:middle line:84%
like the last days or hours of
life, that they talk nonsense,

01:28:01.290 --> 01:28:04.840 align:middle line:84%
that they're talking but you
can't make any sense of it.

01:28:04.840 --> 01:28:09.840 align:middle line:84%
Now we have a logic that's
going to be able to understand

01:28:09.840 --> 01:28:12.980 align:middle line:84%
those enigmatic
conversations of the dying

01:28:12.980 --> 01:28:18.070 align:middle line:84%
so that we can actually sort of
follow people as they go across

01:28:18.070 --> 01:28:20.120 align:middle line:84%
into this other
state of existence.

01:28:20.120 --> 01:28:22.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I have heard that
from various hospice workers.

01:28:22.750 --> 01:28:26.670 align:middle line:84%
That I had the experience
of watching my husband's

01:28:26.670 --> 01:28:30.560 align:middle line:84%
great grandmother pass, and--
peacefully in the house.

01:28:30.560 --> 01:28:34.840 align:middle line:84%
And we, through the days
leading up to her final passing,

01:28:34.840 --> 01:28:39.670 align:middle line:84%
was communicating with
different people beyond.

01:28:39.670 --> 01:28:42.922 align:middle line:84%
And the hospice worker said
this is very, very common,

01:28:42.922 --> 01:28:44.380 align:middle line:84%
which we heard in
one of the clips.

01:28:44.380 --> 01:28:45.588 align:middle line:90%
>>MOODY: Oh, yes, absolutely.

01:28:45.588 --> 01:28:48.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this is what you
hear, and you're tracking this.

01:28:48.130 --> 01:28:50.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MOODY: Yes, we'll actually
be able now to track this.

